WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:04.840 --> 00:00:06.340
Good evening, friends.

00:00:06.340 --> 00:00:07.390
I'm Homi Bhabha.

00:00:07.390 --> 00:00:12.970
I direct the Mahindra Humanities
Center here at Harvard.

00:00:12.970 --> 00:00:17.290
And it's a great pleasure to
invite you and welcome you

00:00:17.290 --> 00:00:23.810
to one of our Writers Speak
sessions for this semester.

00:00:23.810 --> 00:00:31.720
Writers Speak is a platform of
the Humanities Center very ably

00:00:31.720 --> 00:00:40.330
headed by my dear, beloved
friend Claire Messud.

00:00:40.330 --> 00:00:48.340
Who is professor of the practice
of writing and is a wonderful--

00:00:48.340 --> 00:00:51.770
and I say this without
any prejudice whatsoever--

00:00:51.770 --> 00:00:58.660
wonderful, reflective,
beautiful novelist.

00:00:58.660 --> 00:01:03.760
And it's been one of the
great pleasures of my tenure

00:01:03.760 --> 00:01:08.740
as director of the Center
to work with Claire

00:01:08.740 --> 00:01:10.070
on a number of occasions.

00:01:13.790 --> 00:01:17.900
It is actually a
tribute to Claire,

00:01:17.900 --> 00:01:23.180
that since she started working
with us to set up the Writers

00:01:23.180 --> 00:01:28.940
Speak series, she
has chosen writers

00:01:28.940 --> 00:01:35.570
to come to the campus who
effortlessly represent

00:01:35.570 --> 00:01:43.970
a large variety of communities,
ethnicities, and cultures.

00:01:43.970 --> 00:01:50.120
There has been no forced
identitarian agenda here.

00:01:50.120 --> 00:01:53.840
She has just chosen writers who
she thought were significant.

00:01:53.840 --> 00:01:55.880
We've discussed them.

00:01:55.880 --> 00:01:57.810
And she's brought them.

00:01:57.810 --> 00:02:02.886
And that has really enriched
the archive of our thinking

00:02:02.886 --> 00:02:04.010
about contemporary writing.

00:02:07.040 --> 00:02:11.480
So often the discussion is
about bringing writers of color

00:02:11.480 --> 00:02:14.420
or bringing writers
who lack all color.

00:02:14.420 --> 00:02:18.670
But Claire has a
fabulous instinct

00:02:18.670 --> 00:02:21.950
of bringing great writers,
fascinating writers.

00:02:21.950 --> 00:02:23.990
And as it happens,
they have come

00:02:23.990 --> 00:02:28.940
from almost every continent
and many countries.

00:02:28.940 --> 00:02:31.250
And they're writers
of all colors.

00:02:31.250 --> 00:02:36.920
In fact, the slightly tinged
lilac ones were my favorite.

00:02:36.920 --> 00:02:41.900
So Claire, thank you very much
for this great Catholic vision

00:02:41.900 --> 00:02:47.270
of what writing today is about
and where the voices come from.

00:02:47.270 --> 00:02:51.230
And in fact, tomorrow,
Richard Price, Edison Julio,

00:02:51.230 --> 00:02:55.410
and Michelle Kwo accompanied
by Claire Messud,

00:02:55.410 --> 00:03:03.410
will be in Emerson 2 1 0 at 6:00
PM speaking to a panel titled,

00:03:03.410 --> 00:03:08.690
"The Words to Say It, Teaching
and Writing and Incarceration."

00:03:08.690 --> 00:03:12.380
Please welcome my friend
and colleague Claire Messud.

00:03:12.380 --> 00:03:17.300
[APPLAUSE]

00:03:17.300 --> 00:03:18.140
Thank you, Homi.

00:03:18.140 --> 00:03:20.580
Thank you, everyone, for coming.

00:03:20.580 --> 00:03:24.260
It's my great pleasure to
introduce Richard this evening

00:03:24.260 --> 00:03:26.860
and to be in conversation.

00:03:26.860 --> 00:03:29.180
And, yes, as Homi
mentioned, there

00:03:29.180 --> 00:03:32.960
are a number of events
around Richard's visit

00:03:32.960 --> 00:03:36.440
and also the visit
of Lorraine Adams.

00:03:36.440 --> 00:03:39.530
And tomorrow, the
six o'clock panel

00:03:39.530 --> 00:03:45.200
will be upstairs involving
also Edison Julio and Michelle

00:03:45.200 --> 00:03:48.080
Kwo in a discussion
about teaching writing

00:03:48.080 --> 00:03:50.720
and incarceration.

00:03:50.720 --> 00:03:51.830
I hope you can make it.

00:03:54.560 --> 00:03:56.600
Now I need my glasses.

00:03:56.600 --> 00:03:58.280
I was saying to
somebody, I don't

00:03:58.280 --> 00:04:00.610
know how many of you are
familiar with Fawlty Towers,

00:04:00.610 --> 00:04:04.760
but this week I am a little bit
like somebody in Fawlty Towers.

00:04:04.760 --> 00:04:07.170
I put on one hat and then
I move into another room

00:04:07.170 --> 00:04:08.216
I put on another hat.

00:04:10.820 --> 00:04:13.310
Next thing, I'll be wearing a
kimono one offering massages,

00:04:13.310 --> 00:04:13.810
whatever.

00:04:16.130 --> 00:04:18.320
As Michiko Kakutani wrote
in her New York Times

00:04:18.320 --> 00:04:21.410
review of Richard Price's
most recent novel, The Whites,

00:04:21.410 --> 00:04:23.720
"Mr. Price has a knack
for using detective

00:04:23.720 --> 00:04:26.240
work the way John Le
Carre has used spy stories

00:04:26.240 --> 00:04:28.400
and tradecraft as a
framework on which

00:04:28.400 --> 00:04:31.460
to build complex
human investigations

00:04:31.460 --> 00:04:34.220
into the human soul."

00:04:34.220 --> 00:04:36.390
Richard Price is the
author of nine novels,

00:04:36.390 --> 00:04:39.020
including The Wanderers,
Clockers, Freedomland,

00:04:39.020 --> 00:04:41.030
Lush Life, and The Whites.

00:04:41.030 --> 00:04:43.040
He's also an
acclaimed scriptwriter

00:04:43.040 --> 00:04:45.440
for both film and television,
whose credits include

00:04:45.440 --> 00:04:50.000
The Color of Money,
1986, Ransom, 1996,

00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:54.260
the series The Wire, 2002, and
last year's Emmy nominated HBO

00:04:54.260 --> 00:04:56.090
series, The Night Of.

00:04:56.090 --> 00:04:59.060
His new show, currently on
air on HBO, is The Deuce.

00:04:59.060 --> 00:05:02.480
He's also a frequent contributor
to the Moth Radio Hour,

00:05:02.480 --> 00:05:06.470
where you can hear him telling
great stories in his own voice.

00:05:06.470 --> 00:05:08.300
Richard Price,
likened by Walter Kern

00:05:08.300 --> 00:05:10.610
to Raymond Chandler
and Saul Bellow,

00:05:10.610 --> 00:05:13.310
is revered for his
extraordinary ear for dialogue.

00:05:13.310 --> 00:05:15.800
Or as James Wood put it
in his review of Lush

00:05:15.800 --> 00:05:18.950
Life, "for his wonderful
mind for dialogue,

00:05:18.950 --> 00:05:21.920
and for his unsurpassed ability
to portray his native New York

00:05:21.920 --> 00:05:23.960
in its infinite diversity."

00:05:23.960 --> 00:05:26.660
His influence over what we now
think of as stellar dialogue

00:05:26.660 --> 00:05:30.710
is so strong and so pervasive
that young readers and viewers

00:05:30.710 --> 00:05:32.660
might be forgiven for
failing to appreciate

00:05:32.660 --> 00:05:34.640
Price's profound originality.

00:05:34.640 --> 00:05:36.500
He changed our understanding.

00:05:36.500 --> 00:05:39.320
And now we think of his
dialogue as the standard

00:05:39.320 --> 00:05:41.902
that we all try to meet.

00:05:41.902 --> 00:05:44.360
As Michael Connelly wrote in
his New York Times Book Review

00:05:44.360 --> 00:05:47.510
of The Whites, it is,
quote, "a work of reportage

00:05:47.510 --> 00:05:49.550
as much as it is
a work of fiction.

00:05:49.550 --> 00:05:51.420
That's what makes it important.

00:05:51.420 --> 00:05:53.090
It tells it like it is.

00:05:53.090 --> 00:05:55.190
It provides insight
and knowledge,

00:05:55.190 --> 00:05:58.010
both rare qualities in the
killing fields of the crime

00:05:58.010 --> 00:05:59.540
novel."

00:05:59.540 --> 00:06:01.790
Frequently using the police
or crime novel as a frame,

00:06:01.790 --> 00:06:04.850
Price has explored large social
issues from the crack epidemic

00:06:04.850 --> 00:06:07.430
to the changed economy of New
York City in the first decade

00:06:07.430 --> 00:06:10.250
of this century, from the
intricacies of family histories

00:06:10.250 --> 00:06:13.160
and dynamics in The Whites
to the psychological toll

00:06:13.160 --> 00:06:15.770
of incarceration
in The Night Of.

00:06:15.770 --> 00:06:18.440
His work is suffused with
a near Shakespearean verbal

00:06:18.440 --> 00:06:19.250
inventiveness.

00:06:19.250 --> 00:06:21.140
Or is it attentiveness?

00:06:21.140 --> 00:06:24.530
A sense of life's absurdity and
humor, a surprising tenderness

00:06:24.530 --> 00:06:26.120
for the foibles
and vulnerabilities

00:06:26.120 --> 00:06:28.490
of his characters, and
an amazing accuracy

00:06:28.490 --> 00:06:30.950
when it comes to human
behavior, from the smallest

00:06:30.950 --> 00:06:33.350
gestures on up.

00:06:33.350 --> 00:06:36.060
Writing good fiction is
like being a safecracker.

00:06:36.060 --> 00:06:39.110
A writer is listening
for the tiniest clicks.

00:06:39.110 --> 00:06:41.720
No writer listens better
than Richard Price.

00:06:41.720 --> 00:06:44.510
And no writer better transforms
that deceptively humble

00:06:44.510 --> 00:06:48.260
activity in superlative
compelling storytelling.

00:06:48.260 --> 00:06:51.200
He takes narratives with which
we're familiar and returns them

00:06:51.200 --> 00:06:55.000
to us each time as something
illuminating and surprising,

00:06:55.000 --> 00:06:59.050
enacting Ezra Pound's
exhortation to make it new.

00:06:59.050 --> 00:07:01.310
It is a privilege
and a great pleasure

00:07:01.310 --> 00:07:02.800
to welcome Richard Price.

00:07:02.800 --> 00:07:03.558
Thank you.

00:07:03.558 --> 00:07:07.230
[APPLAUSE]

00:07:07.230 --> 00:07:08.740
Thank you for that introduction.

00:07:08.740 --> 00:07:12.840
That was a privilege.

00:07:12.840 --> 00:07:14.420
Thank you.

00:07:14.420 --> 00:07:16.920
So Richard will
read, but we thought

00:07:16.920 --> 00:07:18.610
we may chat a little first.

00:07:18.610 --> 00:07:19.110
Yeah.

00:07:19.110 --> 00:07:19.740
A tad.

00:07:19.740 --> 00:07:21.180
A tad, a tad bit.

00:07:25.860 --> 00:07:31.590
One thing I wondered about,
because we talked about it

00:07:31.590 --> 00:07:36.300
in my class, in
one of my classes,

00:07:36.300 --> 00:07:42.390
if you took the dead
bodies out of your fiction

00:07:42.390 --> 00:07:44.330
you would win every prize.

00:07:47.610 --> 00:07:50.574
And so, I don't know if
that's ever occurred to you.

00:07:50.574 --> 00:07:52.490
But that was something
we were thinking about.

00:07:52.490 --> 00:07:55.170
We were thinking
that actually what

00:07:55.170 --> 00:08:03.250
you do in writing
American society is

00:08:03.250 --> 00:08:05.520
of have such a high level.

00:08:05.520 --> 00:08:08.370
And you do get a lot of acclaim.

00:08:08.370 --> 00:08:12.770
But I feel as though, I don't
know if you get the big prizes.

00:08:12.770 --> 00:08:14.741
Do you know what I'm saying?

00:08:14.741 --> 00:08:15.240
Yeah.

00:08:15.240 --> 00:08:17.790
Oh, yeah.

00:08:17.790 --> 00:08:19.800
And I wondered if
that was a choice?

00:08:19.800 --> 00:08:23.590
Whether you thought, this is
what I want to write about

00:08:23.590 --> 00:08:27.270
and this is the way I do it.

00:08:27.270 --> 00:08:33.059
I was wondering, how the
elements of genre, if you will,

00:08:33.059 --> 00:08:36.480
are important to
you as a writer?

00:08:36.480 --> 00:08:39.840
They're convenient and
they're a pain in the ass.

00:08:39.840 --> 00:08:42.780
Because the minute you
use the word "genre,"

00:08:42.780 --> 00:08:45.240
a genre has rules.

00:08:45.240 --> 00:08:48.810
And in the crime,
mystery genre, you

00:08:48.810 --> 00:08:52.470
have a hero, or an
anti-hero more likely.

00:08:52.470 --> 00:08:56.730
You have a bad guy, or a
group of bad guys, good, bad.

00:08:56.730 --> 00:08:59.300
You show off that
nobody's really all good

00:08:59.300 --> 00:09:00.870
or really all bad a little bit.

00:09:00.870 --> 00:09:02.640
But there are rules.

00:09:02.640 --> 00:09:06.750
You can't walk out of there
without justice served.

00:09:06.750 --> 00:09:12.210
And you're like
moody Marlboro man,

00:09:12.210 --> 00:09:17.520
half Nordic, half
Chandleresque guy

00:09:17.520 --> 00:09:21.600
with the busted Venetian blinds
and the bottle of old overcoat

00:09:21.600 --> 00:09:23.010
whiskey in his bottom drawer.

00:09:25.865 --> 00:09:26.490
I'll be honest.

00:09:29.760 --> 00:09:35.460
My first book that I would
say I reported was Clockers.

00:09:35.460 --> 00:09:39.690
And I was working on
that from 1988 to 19--

00:09:39.690 --> 00:09:40.860
it came out in '92.

00:09:44.130 --> 00:09:46.590
I had written four
books, which are based

00:09:46.590 --> 00:09:49.870
on my own human experience.

00:09:49.870 --> 00:09:51.400
But I was 32.

00:09:51.400 --> 00:09:55.090
I didn't have all
that much to say.

00:09:55.090 --> 00:09:58.230
And I just felt like I
wrote myself into a corner.

00:09:58.230 --> 00:10:01.830
And through a number
of circumstances,

00:10:01.830 --> 00:10:06.090
I found myself more in the
world than I had ever been.

00:10:06.090 --> 00:10:09.540
I was haunted by
my own bad cocaine

00:10:09.540 --> 00:10:12.600
habit of the early '80s.

00:10:12.600 --> 00:10:18.360
I wound up teaching at a day
top village, which is sort

00:10:18.360 --> 00:10:22.890
of a residential drug center.

00:10:22.890 --> 00:10:27.590
Pro bono teaching
fiction writing to kids.

00:10:27.590 --> 00:10:33.120
And I found myself, after having
written a movie, Sea of Love,

00:10:33.120 --> 00:10:35.640
it came out in '86
with Al Pacino,

00:10:35.640 --> 00:10:38.430
I found myself in
the company of cops.

00:10:38.430 --> 00:10:40.270
And being with cops--

00:10:40.270 --> 00:10:45.490
there's no judgment, good,
bad, or indifferent--

00:10:45.490 --> 00:10:49.230
the stuff you're allowed
to see of the world

00:10:49.230 --> 00:10:57.150
when you're with cops really
pulled me out of my inner,

00:10:57.150 --> 00:10:59.670
I wonder as I wander books.

00:10:59.670 --> 00:11:04.060
And I became addicted to
going out into the field,

00:11:04.060 --> 00:11:09.790
so to speak, and finding a
story larger than myself.

00:11:09.790 --> 00:11:10.630
I loved it.

00:11:10.630 --> 00:11:13.440
I just loved it so
much that I really

00:11:13.440 --> 00:11:18.130
wanted to write stories
not about me but--

00:11:18.130 --> 00:11:21.690
everything, every novel
is an autobiography.

00:11:21.690 --> 00:11:23.280
I think crossword
puzzles, you'll

00:11:23.280 --> 00:11:25.560
find autobiography in
there from the person

00:11:25.560 --> 00:11:28.350
who made up the clues.

00:11:28.350 --> 00:11:30.270
I figured, there's
enough of me just

00:11:30.270 --> 00:11:32.940
having a narrative voice here.

00:11:32.940 --> 00:11:36.540
And I also found, as
my landscapes in books

00:11:36.540 --> 00:11:42.500
became more and more
panoramic, like in Lush Life

00:11:42.500 --> 00:11:44.940
it was about Lower
East Siders live

00:11:44.940 --> 00:11:46.980
not in the days of
[INAUDIBLE] sleep

00:11:46.980 --> 00:11:53.490
but in the days of
post-crack yuppification.

00:11:53.490 --> 00:11:56.430
And all the worlds
involved in it--

00:11:56.430 --> 00:11:59.730
there were seven
separate planets.

00:11:59.730 --> 00:12:02.850
And I didn't want to
write a travelogue.

00:12:02.850 --> 00:12:07.110
And then I realized, if you
follow criminal investigation,

00:12:07.110 --> 00:12:09.360
it provides you with
a spine that you

00:12:09.360 --> 00:12:13.870
can ride to a very complex
landscape, like a white horse.

00:12:13.870 --> 00:12:17.010
Because criminal
investigations are orderly.

00:12:17.010 --> 00:12:19.030
This happens, they're
chronological.

00:12:19.030 --> 00:12:19.980
They makes sense.

00:12:19.980 --> 00:12:21.661
If you talk to
this person, well,

00:12:21.661 --> 00:12:23.160
if you talk to this
person, then you

00:12:23.160 --> 00:12:24.990
need to talk to that person.

00:12:24.990 --> 00:12:28.140
And that person might be a
Fujinese Chinese person walking

00:12:28.140 --> 00:12:31.050
by, that person might
be an entrepreneur

00:12:31.050 --> 00:12:36.990
circa the early 2000s
opening up a hip restaurant.

00:12:36.990 --> 00:12:38.760
The third person
might be a woman

00:12:38.760 --> 00:12:41.460
who lives in a housing
project around the corner.

00:12:41.460 --> 00:12:47.490
Fourth person might be an
old Talmudic scholar davening

00:12:47.490 --> 00:12:51.450
on the Lower East Side.

00:12:51.450 --> 00:12:57.090
And I just got addicted
to taking on landscapes

00:12:57.090 --> 00:13:00.720
and using the cleanness of
a criminal investigation.

00:13:04.860 --> 00:13:07.860
And like I said, I didn't
like or dislike cops.

00:13:07.860 --> 00:13:10.960
Cops are like people.

00:13:10.960 --> 00:13:13.130
They even are people.

00:13:13.130 --> 00:13:15.540
They're like people.

00:13:15.540 --> 00:13:16.800
I'm joking.

00:13:16.800 --> 00:13:20.310
I'm not a police buff.

00:13:20.310 --> 00:13:24.450
I don't automatically take
the police point of view

00:13:24.450 --> 00:13:28.380
in dramatic situations.

00:13:28.380 --> 00:13:31.710
You can't count on me
to back up your opinion

00:13:31.710 --> 00:13:33.110
just because I write about.

00:13:37.770 --> 00:13:41.140
And what happens is, I
just love that stuff.

00:13:41.140 --> 00:13:44.400
And I just love using
that wherever I go.

00:13:44.400 --> 00:13:48.420
So there's bodies in
it, and there's crime.

00:13:48.420 --> 00:13:50.970
But I don't want to
protest too much,

00:13:50.970 --> 00:13:54.330
but how many great novels had
crimes in them as their basis?

00:13:54.330 --> 00:13:57.930
Not to compare
myself with anybody.

00:13:57.930 --> 00:13:59.020
Let's start with Dreiser.

00:13:59.020 --> 00:14:01.350
Sorry, I said I
wouldn't do that.

00:14:05.040 --> 00:14:09.000
Then all of a sudden, you've got
a reputation as a crime writer.

00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:10.770
And I went, whoa,
wait, wait, wait.

00:14:10.770 --> 00:14:11.820
That's not it.

00:14:11.820 --> 00:14:12.780
I don't feel like I am.

00:14:12.780 --> 00:14:16.620
But I feel like I have to
step away from that just

00:14:16.620 --> 00:14:22.170
to write myself as not a
genre writer, which I never

00:14:22.170 --> 00:14:22.860
felt I was.

00:14:22.860 --> 00:14:25.800
When you say, step away,
in what way step away?

00:14:25.800 --> 00:14:28.662
Step away from crime
and punishment.

00:14:28.662 --> 00:14:30.120
You mean in your
work, or just in--

00:14:30.120 --> 00:14:34.260
In my work, in my writing.

00:14:34.260 --> 00:14:36.480
But that means stepping
away from something I love.

00:14:36.480 --> 00:14:40.560
I really have a blast
writing crime and punishment.

00:14:40.560 --> 00:14:43.650
And you've got to like
what you're writing.

00:14:43.650 --> 00:14:45.950
It's like it's like a marriage.

00:14:45.950 --> 00:14:48.510
And you shouldn't
marry this individual

00:14:48.510 --> 00:14:51.540
because it'll be good for you,
like oatmeal is good for you.

00:14:51.540 --> 00:14:55.020
So it's a big compromise
between my fun

00:14:55.020 --> 00:14:58.740
and but I don't want
to get seduced into it.

00:14:58.740 --> 00:15:02.070
I want to show people
that I can write.

00:15:02.070 --> 00:15:05.310
So the minute you start thinking
about readers as opposed

00:15:05.310 --> 00:15:09.060
to yourself, you get
lost in the woods.

00:15:09.060 --> 00:15:12.180
And you can't figure out,
what do I really want to do.

00:15:12.180 --> 00:15:13.050
Time is tight.

00:15:13.050 --> 00:15:15.120
I'm 67.

00:15:15.120 --> 00:15:19.170
It's not like I have 50
years of writing ahead of me.

00:15:19.170 --> 00:15:20.440
So it's complicated.

00:15:20.440 --> 00:15:22.680
I'm wrestling with
this every day.

00:15:22.680 --> 00:15:25.050
If you've never felt--

00:15:25.050 --> 00:15:27.280
I wanted to put to you
because many years ago,

00:15:27.280 --> 00:15:32.550
the writer [INAUDIBLE] said
to me-- it wasn't just me,

00:15:32.550 --> 00:15:35.340
it was in a room full of
people, but whatever--

00:15:35.340 --> 00:15:37.230
he said, you can make
up the characters

00:15:37.230 --> 00:15:40.870
or you can make up the plot,
but you can't make up both.

00:15:40.870 --> 00:15:42.576
And I think a lot about that.

00:15:42.576 --> 00:15:43.950
And I think, do
I agree with him?

00:15:43.950 --> 00:15:45.324
I don't know if
I agree with him.

00:15:45.324 --> 00:15:51.360
But it's certainly true
that any work of fiction

00:15:51.360 --> 00:15:54.030
is a balance between
freedom and constraint.

00:15:54.030 --> 00:15:57.794
And when you say
that having a crime

00:15:57.794 --> 00:15:59.460
gives you a sort of
white horse that you

00:15:59.460 --> 00:16:04.160
can ride through a landscape
it gives you a structure,

00:16:04.160 --> 00:16:05.580
it gives you constraint.

00:16:05.580 --> 00:16:09.820
And if those constraints are
in fact liberating for you--

00:16:09.820 --> 00:16:12.510
you've written novels, as I
said in the introduction, that

00:16:12.510 --> 00:16:16.500
are actually about all these
very different bigger social

00:16:16.500 --> 00:16:18.510
issues.

00:16:18.510 --> 00:16:23.500
There may happen to
be corpses in them

00:16:23.500 --> 00:16:26.520
or investigations in them.

00:16:26.520 --> 00:16:28.980
But it hasn't stopped you
writing about anything.

00:16:35.420 --> 00:16:38.190
Why would you step away from it?

00:16:38.190 --> 00:16:40.230
Because of what you just said.

00:16:40.230 --> 00:16:45.142
If it wasn't for bodies
I might be regarded more.

00:16:45.142 --> 00:16:45.975
But you are regard--

00:16:45.975 --> 00:16:46.760
I feel you are.

00:16:46.760 --> 00:16:48.090
Well, that's a problem with me.

00:16:48.090 --> 00:16:50.511
It's like, stay with yourself.

00:16:50.511 --> 00:16:52.260
But they're saying
this and this about me.

00:16:52.260 --> 00:16:53.135
Well, I'll show them.

00:16:53.135 --> 00:16:54.510
And that's where
you get screwed,

00:16:54.510 --> 00:16:55.575
where you screw yourself.

00:17:00.600 --> 00:17:06.839
I'm the type of person that
reviews are dangerous to me.

00:17:06.839 --> 00:17:08.550
Much less so than ever before.

00:17:08.550 --> 00:17:13.440
But I'm easily influenced.

00:17:13.440 --> 00:17:17.099
Like in third grade,
it'd be, well, he just

00:17:17.099 --> 00:17:17.959
follows this crowd.

00:17:17.959 --> 00:17:19.584
I'd really like to
see little Richard--

00:17:22.800 --> 00:17:25.470
it's a struggle every day.

00:17:25.470 --> 00:17:30.180
Part of the struggle is
you have to really enjoy

00:17:30.180 --> 00:17:33.960
what you're doing to do it.

00:17:33.960 --> 00:17:37.070
And I write about
certain people.

00:17:37.070 --> 00:17:40.560
And this is going to sound
bizarre, and very unliterary,

00:17:40.560 --> 00:17:43.280
but I write about the
people I write about

00:17:43.280 --> 00:17:45.660
because I can make
them funny, not

00:17:45.660 --> 00:17:49.680
to sacrifice to the
complexity of their humanity.

00:17:49.680 --> 00:17:54.900
I know how to make working
class urban people.

00:17:54.900 --> 00:17:58.260
I know how to write
about urban underdog.

00:17:58.260 --> 00:17:59.940
I know how to write about cops.

00:17:59.940 --> 00:18:05.250
I know how to write about
put together families

00:18:05.250 --> 00:18:06.915
on a certain level of society.

00:18:09.930 --> 00:18:11.730
I just love being
able to freedom,

00:18:11.730 --> 00:18:14.970
to make the dialogue fly.

00:18:14.970 --> 00:18:17.160
Humor doesn't come
out of it ha, ha.

00:18:17.160 --> 00:18:19.344
Humor comes out of
sheer recognition.

00:18:19.344 --> 00:18:21.510
And it's a surprise when
you find yourself grinning,

00:18:21.510 --> 00:18:22.650
like I knew that.

00:18:22.650 --> 00:18:25.104
I didn't know I knew
that until I read that.

00:18:25.104 --> 00:18:26.520
But once I read
that, I recognized

00:18:26.520 --> 00:18:27.900
I knew that all along.

00:18:27.900 --> 00:18:32.430
So for me, it's
the beauty of hope,

00:18:32.430 --> 00:18:35.700
people being able to
recognize certain elements

00:18:35.700 --> 00:18:38.500
of their personality
and their situation.

00:18:38.500 --> 00:18:41.190
I don't know how to make
patent engineers funny.

00:18:41.190 --> 00:18:43.814
I don't know how to make
corporate lawyers funny.

00:18:43.814 --> 00:18:45.730
I don't know how to make
brain surgeons funny.

00:18:48.440 --> 00:18:51.030
Well, you should write about
a higher level of society

00:18:51.030 --> 00:18:54.710
because then it would show you
have this big span, blah, blah.

00:18:54.710 --> 00:18:55.710
I just have to have fun.

00:18:55.710 --> 00:18:57.751
If I'm not having fun
nobody's going to have fun.

00:18:57.751 --> 00:18:59.440
If I don't enjoy
writing this nobody's

00:18:59.440 --> 00:19:00.930
going to enjoy reading this.

00:19:00.930 --> 00:19:01.470
I hear you.

00:19:01.470 --> 00:19:02.210
Life is short.

00:19:02.210 --> 00:19:02.710
I agree.

00:19:06.300 --> 00:19:11.650
You've said before that
place is a character for you.

00:19:11.650 --> 00:19:13.200
And that your start with place.

00:19:13.200 --> 00:19:18.010
Or that place is one of
the fundamental elements.

00:19:18.010 --> 00:19:28.050
And I wonder, given the sort of
breadth and range of, in a way,

00:19:28.050 --> 00:19:32.040
thematically of the subjects
that you've written about,

00:19:32.040 --> 00:19:34.350
whether you choose
a place with it--

00:19:34.350 --> 00:19:36.750
Did you choose,
say, for Lush Life,

00:19:36.750 --> 00:19:38.880
did you choose the Lower
East Side because of the--

00:19:38.880 --> 00:19:40.650
Every place is a choice.

00:19:40.650 --> 00:19:46.230
Because let's say you have
three key characters in a story.

00:19:46.230 --> 00:19:49.260
One of those
characters is location.

00:19:49.260 --> 00:19:51.690
I'd like to know
going into the book

00:19:51.690 --> 00:19:54.540
at least I have one of
my characters down cold.

00:19:54.540 --> 00:20:00.450
So I will always write
about urban environments.

00:20:00.450 --> 00:20:05.430
Look, if I grew up by the
sea I'd be writing sea books.

00:20:05.430 --> 00:20:07.320
If I grew up in the
mountains it would all

00:20:07.320 --> 00:20:08.220
take place in the mountains.

00:20:08.220 --> 00:20:10.560
If I grew up in the Great
Plains, et cetera, et cetera.

00:20:10.560 --> 00:20:14.370
I grew up in the
city, and I love it.

00:20:17.010 --> 00:20:18.960
For all the anxiety
and hair pulling

00:20:18.960 --> 00:20:24.780
that goes through making a
book from beginning to end,

00:20:24.780 --> 00:20:26.880
you got to love
what you're doing.

00:20:26.880 --> 00:20:29.730
You got to love the people
you're writing about,

00:20:29.730 --> 00:20:33.450
even if whatever
you making them,

00:20:33.450 --> 00:20:39.370
blacker than black in
terms of devil souls,

00:20:39.370 --> 00:20:41.280
you've got to love
them in some way.

00:20:41.280 --> 00:20:44.050
And I've got to love my world.

00:20:44.050 --> 00:20:45.420
And I got to love my people.

00:20:48.330 --> 00:20:50.689
When I was younger before--

00:20:50.689 --> 00:20:52.980
when I was writing my first
four books I was in my 20s.

00:20:55.500 --> 00:20:58.370
They're very deep books.

00:20:58.370 --> 00:20:58.870
Not.

00:21:00.800 --> 00:21:02.925
I started feeling, well,
I don't want to reputation

00:21:02.925 --> 00:21:06.380
as this d'ese, d'em,
d'ose dialogue writer.

00:21:06.380 --> 00:21:07.430
I'm going to show them.

00:21:07.430 --> 00:21:10.350
I'm going to write about
the Spanish Armada.

00:21:10.350 --> 00:21:13.260
And I'm going to do it so, wow,
he can write about anything.

00:21:13.260 --> 00:21:14.670
Never happened.

00:21:14.670 --> 00:21:16.390
I was probably drunk
at the time, but--

00:21:19.260 --> 00:21:23.070
It's all about love.

00:21:23.070 --> 00:21:25.830
I'm sounding like
a broken record.

00:21:25.830 --> 00:21:28.260
But it's a long haul, a book.

00:21:28.260 --> 00:21:30.670
It's like getting married.

00:21:30.670 --> 00:21:33.000
You got to love the
hell out of the person

00:21:33.000 --> 00:21:36.840
that you're joining with
for a number of years.

00:21:40.440 --> 00:21:42.990
There are lots of things
I want to ask you.

00:21:42.990 --> 00:21:46.940
But maybe, what about
starting with dialogue.

00:21:46.940 --> 00:21:51.510
And to what extent is
that just something

00:21:51.510 --> 00:21:54.000
you can do in your sleep?

00:21:54.000 --> 00:21:59.550
To what extent is that something
that you work at relentlessly?

00:21:59.550 --> 00:22:05.460
To what extent is it actually
just reported speech?

00:22:05.460 --> 00:22:13.841
Listen, I always liked making
up people talking to each other.

00:22:13.841 --> 00:22:15.340
I remember when I
was six years old,

00:22:15.340 --> 00:22:19.050
there was a girl I had
a crush on, first grade.

00:22:19.050 --> 00:22:21.930
And I would never talk to
her in a billion years.

00:22:21.930 --> 00:22:26.070
But I would I would lay in
bed before I went to sleep,

00:22:26.070 --> 00:22:29.800
and she was being attacked
by a space monster.

00:22:29.800 --> 00:22:32.430
And she was going,
help, Richard, help.

00:22:32.430 --> 00:22:33.610
And I'd go, I'll save you.

00:22:33.610 --> 00:22:35.130
But then I would
have a big dialogue

00:22:35.130 --> 00:22:36.710
with the space monster.

00:22:36.710 --> 00:22:39.470
Don't you touch
Freida Jankolowitz.

00:22:39.470 --> 00:22:41.200
I will touch anybody I want.

00:22:41.200 --> 00:22:42.070
No.

00:22:42.070 --> 00:22:43.300
We'd start arguing.

00:22:43.300 --> 00:22:45.370
And Freida would go, Hello.

00:22:45.370 --> 00:22:46.980
I'm drifting out in space.

00:22:46.980 --> 00:22:48.360
I just get so caught up.

00:22:48.360 --> 00:22:51.310
And I would say this and
the monster would say that.

00:22:51.310 --> 00:22:54.150
So it's just this intuitive
thing that I just liked.

00:22:57.120 --> 00:23:03.340
And I was intimidated by
Warner's English Grammar

00:23:03.340 --> 00:23:04.410
Handbook.

00:23:04.410 --> 00:23:07.840
It was the bane
of my adolescence.

00:23:07.840 --> 00:23:11.020
And I just had an ear.

00:23:11.020 --> 00:23:12.990
Like some people have--

00:23:12.990 --> 00:23:19.060
always compared
to being a runner.

00:23:19.060 --> 00:23:20.920
You can't teach anybody.

00:23:20.920 --> 00:23:23.350
People run fast or they don't.

00:23:23.350 --> 00:23:27.610
You can fine tune, you can
shave a second or two at best

00:23:27.610 --> 00:23:29.800
off their times.

00:23:29.800 --> 00:23:32.410
But you can't teach
someone to run fast.

00:23:32.410 --> 00:23:36.174
And with dialogue, you
just have to have an ear.

00:23:36.174 --> 00:23:38.090
That's the one thing,
the one gift I was given

00:23:38.090 --> 00:23:40.470
is I have an ear.

00:23:40.470 --> 00:23:44.146
I remember, it was actual
creative writing class

00:23:44.146 --> 00:23:44.770
in high school.

00:23:44.770 --> 00:23:47.560
Nobody had a creative
writing class at that point.

00:23:47.560 --> 00:23:49.720
And I had to write a story.

00:23:49.720 --> 00:23:52.760
And I tried to make people real.

00:23:52.760 --> 00:23:58.120
And I used the word "damn,"
Like god damn, or damn.

00:23:58.120 --> 00:24:01.170
And the paper came back
to me and was hemorrhaging

00:24:01.170 --> 00:24:02.980
red from the English teacher.

00:24:02.980 --> 00:24:05.860
This is not necessary to
use language like this.

00:24:08.650 --> 00:24:11.680
I always loved the profane.

00:24:11.680 --> 00:24:13.810
I always loved the music.

00:24:13.810 --> 00:24:17.620
That somehow I could put
music into dialogue in a way

00:24:17.620 --> 00:24:22.480
that, I don't know
what to compare it to.

00:24:22.480 --> 00:24:24.730
It was like jazz for me.

00:24:24.730 --> 00:24:25.230
Yeah.

00:24:29.590 --> 00:24:33.100
My whole rhythm came out of--

00:24:33.100 --> 00:24:35.260
Lorraine Adams, who
spoke earlier today,

00:24:35.260 --> 00:24:37.970
has heard this a billion times
because we lived together.

00:24:37.970 --> 00:24:41.720
She's my wife and
I'm her husband.

00:24:41.720 --> 00:24:45.430
And so she hears me,
oh, god that one again.

00:24:45.430 --> 00:24:46.935
The way I found my voice--

00:24:46.935 --> 00:24:49.060
and finding your voice is
the most important thing,

00:24:49.060 --> 00:24:51.010
I think, for novels.

00:24:51.010 --> 00:24:54.720
Because your narrative voice
is a close cousin to dialogue.

00:24:54.720 --> 00:24:57.920
How intimate is the narrator
going to get to the characters?

00:24:57.920 --> 00:24:59.380
How vernacular is
it going to be?

00:24:59.380 --> 00:25:03.010
Lorraine called it a
close third person.

00:25:03.010 --> 00:25:05.530
And that's pretty
much what it is.

00:25:05.530 --> 00:25:07.810
And I tried to find my voice.

00:25:07.810 --> 00:25:12.760
And when I was in high school
in the Bronx I always liked

00:25:12.760 --> 00:25:16.960
social realism because
I don't know anybody

00:25:16.960 --> 00:25:18.970
in Jane Austen's world,
I don't know anybody

00:25:18.970 --> 00:25:20.540
in John Steinbeck's world.

00:25:20.540 --> 00:25:21.805
So it's not just like English.

00:25:24.400 --> 00:25:26.770
I don't know anybody
in Dickens world.

00:25:26.770 --> 00:25:31.600
But when I started reading
James Baldwin, Richard

00:25:31.600 --> 00:25:38.590
Wright, a couple
of other people,

00:25:38.590 --> 00:25:41.590
James T. Farrell, Studs Lonigan,
people that were writing

00:25:41.590 --> 00:25:49.780
about things I walk on and I see
and I breathe, I found myself.

00:25:49.780 --> 00:25:52.240
And it taught me
that my experience is

00:25:52.240 --> 00:25:54.254
valid grounds for literature.

00:25:54.254 --> 00:25:55.420
That was a big breakthrough.

00:25:55.420 --> 00:25:56.020
However--

00:25:56.020 --> 00:25:57.270
And that was in high school?

00:25:57.270 --> 00:25:59.200
Yeah.

00:25:59.200 --> 00:26:04.210
However, the problem was with
social realist novelists,

00:26:04.210 --> 00:26:06.420
for the most part,
some of the names

00:26:06.420 --> 00:26:10.330
I have given you
excluded from this,

00:26:10.330 --> 00:26:13.990
is that's writing
to make a point.

00:26:13.990 --> 00:26:17.740
And it's like sawing wood.

00:26:17.740 --> 00:26:22.300
One fact, another fact,
somebody makes a statement

00:26:22.300 --> 00:26:28.814
that's proving the point or
the social humanitarian point

00:26:28.814 --> 00:26:30.230
that the author
is trying to make.

00:26:30.230 --> 00:26:31.420
There's no magic in it.

00:26:31.420 --> 00:26:33.850
It was just like taking
dull photographs.

00:26:33.850 --> 00:26:36.364
But I clung to that
because I recognized, oh, I

00:26:36.364 --> 00:26:37.030
know that world.

00:26:37.030 --> 00:26:38.710
So, yeah.

00:26:38.710 --> 00:26:45.280
Then I read a book that probably
very few people in this room

00:26:45.280 --> 00:26:46.225
have read.

00:26:46.225 --> 00:26:48.489
It's called Last
Exit to Brooklyn.

00:26:48.489 --> 00:26:50.530
And it was by a writer
who's a Beat writer, named

00:26:50.530 --> 00:26:52.210
Hubert Selby.

00:26:52.210 --> 00:26:55.180
Hubert Selby also wrote about--

00:26:55.180 --> 00:26:57.970
no, wait, god, am I that boring?

00:27:01.690 --> 00:27:03.580
Selby also wrote
about the streets.

00:27:03.580 --> 00:27:06.840
He wrote about Brooklyn, Red
Hook part of Brooklyn, I think,

00:27:06.840 --> 00:27:09.180
or Bay Ridge, somewhere.

00:27:09.180 --> 00:27:13.620
But he was a child of the Beat.

00:27:13.620 --> 00:27:14.500
He was a Beat.

00:27:14.500 --> 00:27:18.610
He was he was a bebop
artist with words.

00:27:18.610 --> 00:27:21.520
So he wrote about the same thing
but he had this like rhythm,

00:27:21.520 --> 00:27:24.280
this like de-de-te-da,
de-de-te-da.

00:27:24.280 --> 00:27:26.710
And he just lifted
all the concrete out

00:27:26.710 --> 00:27:30.970
of the cement of
a social realist.

00:27:30.970 --> 00:27:33.260
It was like he was
playing an instrument.

00:27:33.260 --> 00:27:39.700
And I found a way not to write
like I was using a hammer

00:27:39.700 --> 00:27:41.510
and tongs.

00:27:41.510 --> 00:27:43.600
I was using a saxophone.

00:27:43.600 --> 00:27:48.370
And so when I found my voice
like that, it was so intimate

00:27:48.370 --> 00:27:51.100
and there was no line
between dialogue and prose.

00:27:51.100 --> 00:27:53.800
And it just lifted
me off the ground

00:27:53.800 --> 00:27:55.990
and really allowed me
to get into my dialogue

00:27:55.990 --> 00:28:02.410
and not worry too much, in
a way to tell a full story.

00:28:02.410 --> 00:28:03.099
So--

00:28:03.099 --> 00:28:04.890
I don't even think I
answered the question.

00:28:04.890 --> 00:28:07.380
Well, you did.

00:28:07.380 --> 00:28:08.640
Now I'm curious.

00:28:11.820 --> 00:28:13.290
Where along the
line did you say,

00:28:13.290 --> 00:28:16.470
this is what I'm going to do?

00:28:16.470 --> 00:28:20.340
Somewhere between the
space monster dialogue

00:28:20.340 --> 00:28:24.360
in your bed at night and--

00:28:24.360 --> 00:28:25.670
When I was eight.

00:28:25.670 --> 00:28:27.540
Early.

00:28:27.540 --> 00:28:29.490
Fantasy wise, when I was eight.

00:28:29.490 --> 00:28:31.950
Realistic wise, not
until I graduated college

00:28:31.950 --> 00:28:34.830
and had a choice.

00:28:34.830 --> 00:28:36.960
My grandfather was a
factory worker in Brooklyn.

00:28:36.960 --> 00:28:38.770
Sorry, you got to
hear all this stuff.

00:28:38.770 --> 00:28:40.770
My grandfather was a
factory worker in Brooklyn.

00:28:40.770 --> 00:28:42.600
He was a Russian immigrant.

00:28:42.600 --> 00:28:47.042
And like every Jew in Russia,
he was studying to be a rabbi.

00:28:47.042 --> 00:28:48.750
I don't think just
one person from Russia

00:28:48.750 --> 00:28:50.190
who came over that
was Jewish who

00:28:50.190 --> 00:28:52.440
wasn't studying to be a rabbi.

00:28:52.440 --> 00:28:55.350
Anyway, he was foreman in
a chrome plating factory.

00:28:55.350 --> 00:28:56.670
But he was very literate.

00:28:56.670 --> 00:28:59.730
He read the Russians in Russian.

00:28:59.730 --> 00:29:03.510
And he came over
and he was he was

00:29:03.510 --> 00:29:07.280
an actor and a stagehand with
the Lower East Side Yiddish

00:29:07.280 --> 00:29:09.210
Theater.

00:29:09.210 --> 00:29:11.180
And he would write poems.

00:29:11.180 --> 00:29:14.370
And they would be published
in this mimeographed thing

00:29:14.370 --> 00:29:19.380
for the Brooklyn
YMHA, which is this--

00:29:19.380 --> 00:29:22.890
but there would be poems on
that would be mimeographed

00:29:22.890 --> 00:29:24.450
like this, and it's stapled.

00:29:24.450 --> 00:29:28.739
And it had huge circulation,
I think, 40, 50 copies.

00:29:28.739 --> 00:29:30.280
And I just remember,
when I was eight

00:29:30.280 --> 00:29:32.840
seeing my grandfather's poem.

00:29:32.840 --> 00:29:33.780
Even at eight, after--

00:29:33.780 --> 00:29:35.910
well, that was kind of
corny there, gramps.

00:29:35.910 --> 00:29:41.640
But nonetheless, it had
his name at the bottom.

00:29:41.640 --> 00:29:46.690
And my father revered
my grandfather.

00:29:46.690 --> 00:29:47.440
It was his father.

00:29:47.440 --> 00:29:49.440
Yeah, his father.

00:29:49.440 --> 00:29:52.470
And I looked at my father
looking at my grandfather.

00:29:52.470 --> 00:29:54.810
I said, I want some
of that look too.

00:29:54.810 --> 00:29:58.560
So I decided it was going
to be writer right then.

00:29:58.560 --> 00:30:00.432
But it was always a fantasy.

00:30:00.432 --> 00:30:01.890
When you get older
you want to have

00:30:01.890 --> 00:30:03.530
a specialty, like
the best dancer,

00:30:03.530 --> 00:30:06.830
or the best hair,
the math brain.

00:30:06.830 --> 00:30:10.950
And I just wanted to be
known as the writer, which

00:30:10.950 --> 00:30:13.860
involved pinching my nose
in a library at a table

00:30:13.860 --> 00:30:15.930
where there was a
couple of girls.

00:30:15.930 --> 00:30:18.950
And I went like this hoping
some of them would come up to me

00:30:18.950 --> 00:30:21.450
and say, are you suffering?

00:30:21.450 --> 00:30:22.580
Never happened.

00:30:22.580 --> 00:30:24.390
But my nose really
did get narrower.

00:30:27.380 --> 00:30:28.130
I went to Cornell.

00:30:28.130 --> 00:30:29.640
I got a degree in
labor relations.

00:30:29.640 --> 00:30:33.110
But I took all my electives
in creative writing.

00:30:33.110 --> 00:30:36.180
And I really, really
wanted to be a writer.

00:30:36.180 --> 00:30:39.300
And my father said, look, you
can write in your spare time.

00:30:39.300 --> 00:30:41.670
It could be like your hobby.

00:30:41.670 --> 00:30:45.100
But once you have a serious job
you can write on the weekends.

00:30:45.100 --> 00:30:46.850
And then came time,
what are you going

00:30:46.850 --> 00:30:48.394
to do for graduate school?

00:30:48.394 --> 00:30:50.310
And so I applied to
every-- including Harvard.

00:30:50.310 --> 00:30:53.290
I got for MAT in teaching.

00:30:53.290 --> 00:30:57.100
That lasted about six minutes.

00:30:57.100 --> 00:31:02.310
And the one Master of Fine Arts
school I got into was Columbia.

00:31:02.310 --> 00:31:04.330
And I felt like I
had no right to go.

00:31:04.330 --> 00:31:05.846
I was working class.

00:31:05.846 --> 00:31:07.220
I felt like I had
no right to go.

00:31:07.220 --> 00:31:10.710
My father had a
little hosiery store.

00:31:10.710 --> 00:31:16.410
And he got so exasperated by me
Hamleting all across the floor,

00:31:16.410 --> 00:31:17.550
I don't know what to do.

00:31:17.550 --> 00:31:20.910
And my father finally
said, oh, Jesus Christ,

00:31:20.910 --> 00:31:22.941
go to your stupid
creative writing program.

00:31:22.941 --> 00:31:24.690
If it doesn't work
out, two years from now

00:31:24.690 --> 00:31:27.340
you'll go to law
school, big deal.

00:31:27.340 --> 00:31:30.720
I just remember saying
literally, gee, dad, you

00:31:30.720 --> 00:31:32.090
mean it?

00:31:32.090 --> 00:31:33.810
Boom.

00:31:33.810 --> 00:31:37.740
And once I went
to graduate school

00:31:37.740 --> 00:31:43.050
it was great because
I was surrounded

00:31:43.050 --> 00:31:47.210
by 12 people around a seminar
table about once a week.

00:31:47.210 --> 00:31:51.330
And all 12 of those people,
none of them went to law school.

00:31:51.330 --> 00:31:52.320
We're all here.

00:31:52.320 --> 00:31:54.450
None of them were premed.

00:31:54.450 --> 00:31:57.350
none of them went
to business school.

00:31:57.350 --> 00:31:59.580
Meanwhile, everybody's
friends from college

00:31:59.580 --> 00:32:03.780
were now on their
way with a real job.

00:32:03.780 --> 00:32:05.450
And the worst thing
in the world when

00:32:05.450 --> 00:32:08.820
you're a young writer,
even if you're determined,

00:32:08.820 --> 00:32:10.002
is somebody saying--

00:32:10.002 --> 00:32:11.960
say your a writer, and
somebody says, oh, well,

00:32:11.960 --> 00:32:14.880
what have you written?

00:32:14.880 --> 00:32:16.890
Well, I'm working on this
Spanish Armada novel,

00:32:16.890 --> 00:32:20.720
but I'm waiting
for my translator.

00:32:20.720 --> 00:32:24.500
I want to put it in
17th century Spanish

00:32:24.500 --> 00:32:26.859
and I don't know Spanish.

00:32:26.859 --> 00:32:28.650
Instead of saying,
well, what do you write?

00:32:28.650 --> 00:32:32.550
I could say, well, I'm in the
Master of Fine Arts program

00:32:32.550 --> 00:32:34.485
at Columbia.

00:32:34.485 --> 00:32:39.060
It puts your ego on hold and
it gave you at least two years

00:32:39.060 --> 00:32:42.135
where you weren't mortified
by wanting to be a writer.

00:32:42.135 --> 00:32:43.010
And I got very lucky.

00:32:43.010 --> 00:32:46.830
I published a book
when I was 24.

00:32:46.830 --> 00:32:49.810
So were you still in
the program when you--

00:32:49.810 --> 00:32:52.855
This is the other thing
that's really embarrassing.

00:32:52.855 --> 00:32:53.730
I was in the program.

00:32:53.730 --> 00:32:57.300
I left for a year to go to
Stanford because they had

00:32:57.300 --> 00:33:00.180
a little fellowship
which Columbia didn't.

00:33:00.180 --> 00:33:01.440
Which they still have?

00:33:01.440 --> 00:33:02.100
Yeah.

00:33:02.100 --> 00:33:05.700
I got a $1,500 fellowship,
which at that time,

00:33:05.700 --> 00:33:06.680
you're in the money.

00:33:06.680 --> 00:33:07.305
That's cabbage.

00:33:12.540 --> 00:33:14.700
And I came back from Columbia.

00:33:14.700 --> 00:33:17.490
I was taking a class or
two, finishing a seminar,

00:33:17.490 --> 00:33:19.920
and I published my first
novel, The Wanderers.

00:33:19.920 --> 00:33:21.540
Then everybody hated you.

00:33:21.540 --> 00:33:22.710
Well--

00:33:22.710 --> 00:33:24.120
No?

00:33:24.120 --> 00:33:25.860
Probably.

00:33:25.860 --> 00:33:30.840
But I refused to
quit the program.

00:33:30.840 --> 00:33:33.680
And I published another novel,
and I was still in the program.

00:33:33.680 --> 00:33:36.251
And it's driving
everybody batshit.

00:33:36.251 --> 00:33:38.250
And people said, what,
are you making fun of us?

00:33:38.250 --> 00:33:39.390
The teachers hated me.

00:33:39.390 --> 00:33:41.750
Richard Yates was my teacher.

00:33:41.750 --> 00:33:46.290
And in when he did the roll
call he said, who's Price?

00:33:46.290 --> 00:33:48.660
Oh, you're a billion
dollar bonus baby.

00:33:51.500 --> 00:33:53.010
What I finally
realized, the reason

00:33:53.010 --> 00:33:55.740
why I stayed in that
program because I

00:33:55.740 --> 00:33:59.110
wanted a master's
degree in fine arts.

00:33:59.110 --> 00:34:02.490
I was the first person ever
go to college in my family.

00:34:02.490 --> 00:34:05.120
And I wasn't even
thinking about it.

00:34:05.120 --> 00:34:07.410
I wanted that MFA
because I was going

00:34:07.410 --> 00:34:13.310
to have checks printed on top it
would say, Richard Price, MFA.

00:34:13.310 --> 00:34:18.780
I was just a working class
thing that I didn't even

00:34:18.780 --> 00:34:23.760
recognize until years
after I finally graduated.

00:34:23.760 --> 00:34:25.639
Did you have the checks printed?

00:34:25.639 --> 00:34:26.140
No.

00:34:26.140 --> 00:34:26.889
It's not too late.

00:34:26.889 --> 00:34:28.920
[INAUDIBLE] a friend who
put PhD on his checks.

00:34:31.630 --> 00:34:32.520
It's not too late.

00:34:32.520 --> 00:34:34.757
You still could.

00:34:34.757 --> 00:34:35.340
Yeah, I guess.

00:34:42.090 --> 00:34:44.190
By the time you
were at university

00:34:44.190 --> 00:34:46.560
you knew you wanted
to go straight--

00:34:46.560 --> 00:34:49.639
the story is you wanted to go
straight on and be a writer.

00:34:49.639 --> 00:34:54.929
And when you wrote
The Wanderers,

00:34:54.929 --> 00:34:57.900
because the official
story is that you wrote

00:34:57.900 --> 00:35:01.050
one chapter, as it were,
that was then published in,

00:35:01.050 --> 00:35:01.970
Halpern published in--

00:35:01.970 --> 00:35:02.470
In Antaeus.

00:35:02.470 --> 00:35:03.630
In Antaeus.

00:35:03.630 --> 00:35:04.500
The class hated it.

00:35:04.500 --> 00:35:08.790
And Dan Halpern, who became
the head of the writing

00:35:08.790 --> 00:35:10.670
program for a while--

00:35:10.670 --> 00:35:13.110
and he was a very well
known and well regarded

00:35:13.110 --> 00:35:16.720
editor, has his own
imprimatur at HarperCollins.

00:35:16.720 --> 00:35:17.880
Echo.

00:35:17.880 --> 00:35:21.120
Echo.

00:35:21.120 --> 00:35:22.740
He came up to me--
the class hated it

00:35:22.740 --> 00:35:25.800
because the first
chapter of The Wanderers

00:35:25.800 --> 00:35:29.910
was about an all-out gang
war between an Italian gang

00:35:29.910 --> 00:35:31.400
and a black gang.

00:35:31.400 --> 00:35:35.050
And I had the Italians win.

00:35:35.050 --> 00:35:38.660
It was the most politically
incorrect thing to do.

00:35:38.660 --> 00:35:42.510
And teacher was
a psychopath, who

00:35:42.510 --> 00:35:45.400
hated the fact that he had
to teach these people half

00:35:45.400 --> 00:35:45.900
his age.

00:35:45.900 --> 00:35:47.880
Was this Richard Yates
or somebody else?

00:35:47.880 --> 00:35:49.290
Yeah, Richard-- no, no, no.

00:35:49.290 --> 00:35:50.900
It was W.B. Yeats.

00:35:50.900 --> 00:35:52.010
No.

00:35:52.010 --> 00:35:53.870
I don't want to say his name.

00:35:53.870 --> 00:35:59.850
But he was the nastiest person,
and charismatic, very funny.

00:35:59.850 --> 00:36:05.760
So you really didn't realize
you have internal injuries

00:36:05.760 --> 00:36:09.570
until you went home.

00:36:09.570 --> 00:36:12.270
But he led this
wolf pack on this,

00:36:12.270 --> 00:36:14.685
and everybody trashed
it in the class.

00:36:14.685 --> 00:36:17.550
And it was the first thing I
ever read in a writing program.

00:36:20.700 --> 00:36:24.300
I can't hardly remember how
I felt. I was like startled

00:36:24.300 --> 00:36:25.930
and I believed everything.

00:36:25.930 --> 00:36:29.250
I also felt like, oh, well.

00:36:29.250 --> 00:36:33.870
And at the end of the
class, Dan Halpern,

00:36:33.870 --> 00:36:36.562
who's taken a fiction
class just because he

00:36:36.562 --> 00:36:38.520
knew he was going to be
an administrator and he

00:36:38.520 --> 00:36:40.603
wanted to see how the whole
writing program worked

00:36:40.603 --> 00:36:41.630
and all the seminars.

00:36:41.630 --> 00:36:46.620
He'd come up to me and he
said, I want to publish.

00:36:46.620 --> 00:36:49.140
I have a magazine and I
want to publish that story.

00:36:49.140 --> 00:36:50.047
I said, how much?

00:36:50.047 --> 00:36:50.880
I didn't even blink.

00:36:50.880 --> 00:36:52.590
I said, how much?

00:36:52.590 --> 00:36:55.340
And he looked at me
and he said, well,

00:36:55.340 --> 00:36:56.702
it's a literary quarterly.

00:36:56.702 --> 00:36:57.910
We don't have a lot of money.

00:36:57.910 --> 00:37:00.640
We don't pay anybody.

00:37:00.640 --> 00:37:01.800
I went, oh.

00:37:01.800 --> 00:37:04.650
I thought when I said how
much, I thought how much do I

00:37:04.650 --> 00:37:06.300
have to pay for him to publish?

00:37:06.300 --> 00:37:07.770
[LAUGHTER]

00:37:07.770 --> 00:37:11.040
He said, well, you will
get seven free copies.

00:37:11.040 --> 00:37:13.377
OK.

00:37:13.377 --> 00:37:14.460
And I couldn't believe it.

00:37:14.460 --> 00:37:16.140
That was my first class.

00:37:16.140 --> 00:37:21.030
But it reminded me, Paul
Schrader, filmmaker,

00:37:21.030 --> 00:37:25.710
once had a movie that opened
at the Locarno Film Festival.

00:37:25.710 --> 00:37:28.150
The Locarno Film Festival has
the largest outdoor screen

00:37:28.150 --> 00:37:29.225
in the world.

00:37:29.225 --> 00:37:30.975
And the film was The
Comfort of Strangers.

00:37:30.975 --> 00:37:34.670
It was based on an
Ian McEwan book.

00:37:34.670 --> 00:37:37.160
And I said, wow, how did it go?

00:37:37.160 --> 00:37:43.060
He said, well, they started
booing in the opening credits

00:37:43.060 --> 00:37:45.600
and they never stopped until
the screen went dark an hour

00:37:45.600 --> 00:37:47.010
and a half later.

00:37:47.010 --> 00:37:48.740
I said, oh, my god,
how did you feel?

00:37:48.740 --> 00:37:52.530
He said, I felt they were wrong.

00:37:52.530 --> 00:37:53.820
I wasn't that bulletproof.

00:37:53.820 --> 00:37:57.180
But there is a little
part of me that went--

00:37:57.180 --> 00:37:58.230
In the workshop?

00:37:58.230 --> 00:38:00.689
Not a very little
part of me that went--

00:38:00.689 --> 00:38:02.230
But it's important
to have that part.

00:38:05.040 --> 00:38:09.270
Anybody wants to be anything
in the arts as a career,

00:38:09.270 --> 00:38:11.580
you need insane confidence.

00:38:14.160 --> 00:38:20.520
Because it's a
loser's option of,

00:38:20.520 --> 00:38:22.320
some day I'm going
to be driving a cab

00:38:22.320 --> 00:38:25.410
but I'm really a novelist.

00:38:25.410 --> 00:38:30.090
But at least I'm making
a good $150 a week

00:38:30.090 --> 00:38:32.700
while I write this
novel for 10 years.

00:38:32.700 --> 00:38:35.370
You really got to
believe in yourself

00:38:35.370 --> 00:38:40.800
to put up with all the
crap that you have to do.

00:38:40.800 --> 00:38:45.030
The most precious thing
a writer can buy is time.

00:38:45.030 --> 00:38:49.290
But I don't know, if didn't
get published so young,

00:38:49.290 --> 00:38:51.750
if it took 10 more years
to publish my first book,

00:38:51.750 --> 00:38:54.780
I don't know if I would
have had the stamina.

00:38:54.780 --> 00:38:56.460
I think I was very
lucky to publish

00:38:56.460 --> 00:39:00.690
early simply because
with my upbringing,

00:39:00.690 --> 00:39:02.190
I don't know if I could take it.

00:39:02.190 --> 00:39:05.410
Visiting my Cornell
roommates, one guy

00:39:05.410 --> 00:39:11.970
is now vice president
at some pudding company,

00:39:11.970 --> 00:39:14.680
or another guy is--

00:39:14.680 --> 00:39:16.130
What's a pudding company?

00:39:16.130 --> 00:39:19.800
The Jell-O pudding, and
Cosby was his client.

00:39:19.800 --> 00:39:21.660
Young Cosby.

00:39:21.660 --> 00:39:22.980
Pudding Pops.

00:39:22.980 --> 00:39:27.320
But people were
doing real things.

00:39:27.320 --> 00:39:28.815
And I don't know
if I could have--

00:39:28.815 --> 00:39:31.140
I would have avoided
every one of them.

00:39:31.140 --> 00:39:32.580
I would've been so--

00:39:32.580 --> 00:39:34.620
oh, Price, you still
writing that book?

00:39:34.620 --> 00:39:36.530
How's it going?

00:39:36.530 --> 00:39:37.800
Well, I'm flying in my taxi.

00:39:40.920 --> 00:39:44.060
that Harry Chapin song.

00:39:44.060 --> 00:39:50.070
I wanted to be some
kind of like a pilot.

00:39:50.070 --> 00:39:52.260
I was driving a
taxi but he still

00:39:52.260 --> 00:39:54.570
get so high when he's stoned.

00:39:54.570 --> 00:39:55.379
It's like that.

00:39:55.379 --> 00:39:56.670
I didn't want to be like this--

00:39:56.670 --> 00:39:58.150
You didn't want to be that guy.

00:39:58.150 --> 00:39:58.650
Yeah.

00:39:58.650 --> 00:39:59.512
I just--

00:39:59.512 --> 00:40:00.660
No.

00:40:00.660 --> 00:40:06.770
So then how did writing for
film, how did that come about?

00:40:06.770 --> 00:40:10.440
And how is that
different for you?

00:40:10.440 --> 00:40:13.650
Well, it's very different.

00:40:13.650 --> 00:40:14.940
I've done a lot of film.

00:40:14.940 --> 00:40:18.510
And now I'm doing a lot of TV.

00:40:18.510 --> 00:40:23.220
And the difference is, when you
write a novel, it's all yours.

00:40:23.220 --> 00:40:26.790
Every decision, every
word, every comma is yours.

00:40:26.790 --> 00:40:30.280
When you're working
on a TV show,

00:40:30.280 --> 00:40:32.250
it's a collaborative medium.

00:40:32.250 --> 00:40:36.880
And you're just one
of a number of people.

00:40:36.880 --> 00:40:39.690
So you write the script.

00:40:39.690 --> 00:40:43.146
And they're going to change the
script for expediency's sake,

00:40:43.146 --> 00:40:45.270
or the budget's too big,
or we lost the main actor.

00:40:45.270 --> 00:40:46.770
We have another
actor but he doesn't

00:40:46.770 --> 00:40:50.370
want to play this type
of guy, change the guy.

00:40:50.370 --> 00:40:55.740
So you write the script,
but as I said ad nauseam,

00:40:55.740 --> 00:41:00.424
it's not a building,
it's a blueprint.

00:41:00.424 --> 00:41:02.340
The building is not going
to be the blueprint.

00:41:02.340 --> 00:41:03.881
The building is
going to be building,

00:41:03.881 --> 00:41:06.120
depending on what kind of
materials they can get,

00:41:06.120 --> 00:41:09.330
how the economy goes, well, we
can't afford all these windows.

00:41:11.890 --> 00:41:17.110
So when you write a movie,
no matter how good it is,

00:41:17.110 --> 00:41:19.170
it's never the
movie that's made,

00:41:19.170 --> 00:41:22.440
and because you don't
have any control over it.

00:41:22.440 --> 00:41:25.800
You're the first one in and
everybody lands on top of you

00:41:25.800 --> 00:41:28.600
in the decision making process.

00:41:28.600 --> 00:41:36.920
And so you could be Shakespeare,
if they had movies back then.

00:41:36.920 --> 00:41:41.892
And you got this great story
about this boy and this girl,

00:41:41.892 --> 00:41:43.850
they go crazy for each
other, blah, blah, blah.

00:41:43.850 --> 00:41:45.900
The families are fighting.

00:41:45.900 --> 00:41:47.970
And that's great.

00:41:47.970 --> 00:41:49.620
But you know what?

00:41:49.620 --> 00:41:53.780
Steven Segal wants to
play the Capulet boss.

00:41:53.780 --> 00:41:57.180
We got a good shot at getting
Brando for the Montague.

00:41:57.180 --> 00:42:00.390
And these kids, I know
they're supposed to be 13,

00:42:00.390 --> 00:42:04.260
but there's this 22-year-old
hot actress named Amber Heard.

00:42:04.260 --> 00:42:09.240
And we really think she
would help the movie.

00:42:09.240 --> 00:42:13.960
And, well, Denzel
wants to play Romeo.

00:42:13.960 --> 00:42:16.830
So we've got to really
age up these characters.

00:42:16.830 --> 00:42:17.920
It's going to happen.

00:42:17.920 --> 00:42:20.130
It's not your choice.

00:42:20.130 --> 00:42:21.300
You're at the mercy.

00:42:21.300 --> 00:42:27.030
So when a movie or a TV
show is a big success,

00:42:27.030 --> 00:42:31.020
and somebody comes to you
and says, I loved your movie.

00:42:31.020 --> 00:42:33.570
I feel like they're
congratulating

00:42:33.570 --> 00:42:37.650
eight people between me and
them because it wasn't my movie,

00:42:37.650 --> 00:42:39.660
it was my script.

00:42:39.660 --> 00:42:43.080
