00:56:12.220 --> 00:56:14.972
going to have the whole history
of Bolivar watch factory.

00:56:14.972 --> 00:56:16.930
So I'm go into Lynn
Nesbit, my agent, and said,

00:56:16.930 --> 00:56:18.300
I'm losing my mind.

00:56:18.300 --> 00:56:19.760
I'm really behind in my bills.

00:56:19.760 --> 00:56:21.134
And she says,
well, why don't you

00:56:21.134 --> 00:56:25.020
write a novel under a
pseudonym, like John Banville

00:56:25.020 --> 00:56:28.320
and Benjamin Black?

00:56:28.320 --> 00:56:33.090
There was this wave of like,
Hi, it's me, but it's not me.

00:56:33.090 --> 00:56:35.430
I'm going to have more fun.

00:56:35.430 --> 00:56:37.350
And so I said, I can
get you as much money

00:56:37.350 --> 00:56:39.900
as you would get
for a screenplay.

00:56:39.900 --> 00:56:40.860
I said, great.

00:56:40.860 --> 00:56:42.662
I'll do it.

00:56:42.662 --> 00:56:44.370
So I figured out some
kind of crime book.

00:56:44.370 --> 00:56:46.580
That was going to be The Whites.

00:56:46.580 --> 00:56:50.040
And she said, oh, by the way, if
it takes more than three months

00:56:50.040 --> 00:56:52.360
to write this thing
it's not worth it.

00:56:52.360 --> 00:56:55.530
I said, got it.

00:56:55.530 --> 00:56:58.540
Cut to four years later.

00:56:58.540 --> 00:57:00.690
The Whites, the end.

00:57:00.690 --> 00:57:05.470
My pants fell off, I'm more
bald on this side of my head

00:57:05.470 --> 00:57:08.070
from pulling my hair out.

00:57:08.070 --> 00:57:10.710
How do you write down--

00:57:10.710 --> 00:57:12.870
you write the way you write.

00:57:12.870 --> 00:57:14.920
No, write stupider.

00:57:14.920 --> 00:57:17.930
Write gliber-er-er.

00:57:17.930 --> 00:57:19.770
And you just write
the way you write.

00:57:19.770 --> 00:57:24.660
And so that was one
hell of a three-month--

00:57:24.660 --> 00:57:26.880
So the book came out.

00:57:26.880 --> 00:57:30.600
And I thought it was a
quote, unquote "genre book."

00:57:30.600 --> 00:57:34.410
And so I really wanted
to keep the pen name

00:57:34.410 --> 00:57:39.600
because I didn't
want this book to be

00:57:39.600 --> 00:57:46.050
judged in comparison with
one of my more serious books.

00:57:46.050 --> 00:57:46.800
I didn't want to--

00:57:49.310 --> 00:57:51.102
How did it feel
different to you?

00:57:51.102 --> 00:57:51.810
I'm just curious.

00:57:51.810 --> 00:57:52.680
Because it's--

00:57:52.680 --> 00:57:55.580
Because it followed the rules.

00:57:55.580 --> 00:57:59.100
That thing of all genres
is that there are rules.

00:57:59.100 --> 00:58:00.570
And if you break
the rules people

00:58:00.570 --> 00:58:01.945
don't know what
the hell this is.

00:58:01.945 --> 00:58:03.600
They don't know what
to call the book.

00:58:03.600 --> 00:58:09.990
Is it a thriller, is it a
philosophical meditation

00:58:09.990 --> 00:58:11.380
on human mortality?

00:58:13.930 --> 00:58:14.760
So I said fine.

00:58:14.760 --> 00:58:16.350
It was part of the easy part.

00:58:16.350 --> 00:58:18.030
This has to happen.

00:58:18.030 --> 00:58:21.210
But how do you write
less complex characters?

00:58:24.780 --> 00:58:28.680
If you don't believe in
good guys and bad guys,

00:58:28.680 --> 00:58:30.100
if what you cherish--

00:58:30.100 --> 00:58:32.620
like every novelist
should cherish

00:58:32.620 --> 00:58:36.290
is the gray not the
black or the white,

00:58:36.290 --> 00:58:40.060
but the complexity of
every biped on earth.

00:58:44.230 --> 00:58:45.910
But I was worried
that because it

00:58:45.910 --> 00:58:49.600
fit the conventions
and the genre,

00:58:49.600 --> 00:58:52.060
let me keep the pen name.

00:58:52.060 --> 00:58:54.040
It's just like a--

00:58:54.040 --> 00:58:56.004
but everybody knew it was me.

00:58:56.004 --> 00:58:57.670
So it was like pulling,
I actually said,

00:58:57.670 --> 00:59:00.500
pulling a rabbit
out of a glass hat.

00:59:00.500 --> 00:59:01.000
Here he is.

00:59:01.000 --> 00:59:02.850
Don't tell anybody.

00:59:02.850 --> 00:59:07.160
[INAUDIBLE] So it is ridiculous.

00:59:07.160 --> 00:59:09.430
Because it said in
the reviews even.

00:59:09.430 --> 00:59:11.450
Well, what happened is
I'd start reading reviews

00:59:11.450 --> 00:59:15.140
and it was like, whoa,
hey, it's a good book.

00:59:15.140 --> 00:59:18.640
I said, hmm, why
did I ever put it--

00:59:18.640 --> 00:59:20.170
But it's a lesser book.

00:59:20.170 --> 00:59:21.930
I honestly think
it's a lesser book.

00:59:21.930 --> 00:59:26.530
As good as it might be, and
just as good as it was received,

00:59:26.530 --> 00:59:30.790
well as it was received, I
think it's a lesser book.

00:59:30.790 --> 00:59:35.200
Because it's about solving, aha,
they're the guys that did it.

00:59:37.780 --> 00:59:42.850
Crime is the only
genre where the reader

00:59:42.850 --> 00:59:45.340
is in competition
with the writer

00:59:45.340 --> 00:59:47.890
because they want to
outsmart the writer.

00:59:47.890 --> 00:59:51.040
And I don't know the difference
between that and word jumbles

00:59:51.040 --> 00:59:55.420
or Friday New York
Times crossword puzzles.

00:59:55.420 --> 00:59:59.447
It's supposed to be you
just surrendered to a book.

00:59:59.447 --> 01:00:01.030
I feel like I
surrendered to this book

01:00:01.030 --> 01:00:02.350
as I surrendered to the others.

01:00:02.350 --> 01:00:07.150
And it's true that it's plotted.

01:00:07.150 --> 01:00:11.140
I you think about a crime novel,
it's got to have a revelation.

01:00:11.140 --> 01:00:12.640
And I hate revelations.

01:00:12.640 --> 01:00:16.930
And I hate answers.

01:00:16.930 --> 01:00:21.030
Because life is open ended.

01:00:21.030 --> 01:00:21.925
There are no answers.

01:00:24.760 --> 01:00:30.040
The crime genre requires
if not immortal answers,

01:00:30.040 --> 01:00:33.070
solutions to the mystery.

01:00:33.070 --> 01:00:36.820
And hopefully, you got
there before the reader did.

01:00:36.820 --> 01:00:41.339
And it's just no way
to run an airline.

01:00:41.339 --> 01:00:42.880
Who the hell wants
to write like that

01:00:42.880 --> 01:00:45.160
when the whole world
is out there in all

01:00:45.160 --> 01:00:49.900
it's unanswerableness?

01:00:49.900 --> 01:00:50.700
Yeah.

01:00:50.700 --> 01:00:53.700
But humanly, the characters
are there and all

01:00:53.700 --> 01:00:55.290
their unanswerableness.

01:00:55.290 --> 01:00:57.960
I try.

01:00:57.960 --> 01:01:04.530
But the point is, this time I
really went right to the genre.

01:01:04.530 --> 01:01:08.340
And that's why it was more of
like, I killed myself on it,

01:01:08.340 --> 01:01:11.129
but it was more like,
well, what I do now?

01:01:11.129 --> 01:01:12.420
And you consult the guide book.

01:01:15.331 --> 01:01:17.830
In a minute we'll open it up
to questions from the audience.

01:01:17.830 --> 01:01:19.820
But I just wanted
to ask you also

01:01:19.820 --> 01:01:23.685
about The Night Of,
which you are not just

01:01:23.685 --> 01:01:28.330
the main writer of,
but also a producer.

01:01:28.330 --> 01:01:31.390
So it's your project,
it was your project--

01:01:31.390 --> 01:01:31.890
Yeah.

01:01:31.890 --> 01:01:32.931
I wrote all the episodes.

01:01:32.931 --> 01:01:36.600
In a way completely
differently perhaps

01:01:36.600 --> 01:01:38.550
from some of your
other television.

01:01:38.550 --> 01:01:42.810
Yes and no because
the co-creator

01:01:42.810 --> 01:01:44.820
was also the director.

01:01:44.820 --> 01:01:46.560
So things will get changed.

01:01:46.560 --> 01:01:47.770
He had more power than I did.

01:01:47.770 --> 01:01:50.560
So he's not only changing
things on the set,

01:01:50.560 --> 01:01:52.620
determining on
circumstances, but he's

01:01:52.620 --> 01:01:54.570
changing things because
he's also a writer,

01:01:54.570 --> 01:01:56.100
he's a screenwriter.

01:01:56.100 --> 01:01:58.770
So the worst thing in
the world is for a writer

01:01:58.770 --> 01:02:01.917
to write for a writer
because they're never going

01:02:01.917 --> 01:02:03.000
to respect what you wrote.

01:02:05.730 --> 01:02:08.160
And things happen.

01:02:08.160 --> 01:02:10.080
I can see the
character a certain way

01:02:10.080 --> 01:02:12.690
but he wants to
cast someone that's

01:02:12.690 --> 01:02:15.300
going to play an
entirely opposite way.

01:02:15.300 --> 01:02:16.590
And it's his decision.

01:02:16.590 --> 01:02:21.180
It's better to hire this
individual and let her

01:02:21.180 --> 01:02:22.940
or him do his thing.

01:02:22.940 --> 01:02:25.180
It will serve the
story so much better.

01:02:25.180 --> 01:02:27.150
I mean, I love what you
wrote, but now we're

01:02:27.150 --> 01:02:30.420
dealing with putting
flesh on the page.

01:02:33.150 --> 01:02:34.260
Yeah, it was mine.

01:02:34.260 --> 01:02:39.700
But there's always this
element of like no, no, no, no

01:02:39.700 --> 01:02:42.040
what do you do, what did you do?

01:02:42.040 --> 01:02:44.380
But then there is
also stuff that you

01:02:44.380 --> 01:02:45.780
didn't write that's in there.

01:02:45.780 --> 01:02:47.910
And you'll go, wow,
he really nailed that.

01:02:47.910 --> 01:02:50.070
I don't even touch that.

01:02:50.070 --> 01:02:52.770
So it's a give and take.

01:02:52.770 --> 01:02:56.280
At best it's a give and take.

01:02:56.280 --> 01:02:58.890
At worst it's all take.

01:02:58.890 --> 01:03:03.040
And you go home with
elephant ears inside out,

01:03:03.040 --> 01:03:06.510
feeling angry and I'll never do
that again, till the next time.

01:03:09.390 --> 01:03:10.950
I realized that
there was a thing way

01:03:10.950 --> 01:03:14.220
back that I wanted to ask you.

01:03:14.220 --> 01:03:16.860
There were two paths in a wood.

01:03:16.860 --> 01:03:23.320
And it was about research,
and how you do your research.

01:03:23.320 --> 01:03:28.320
And you said, it was an
excuse to spend all this time

01:03:28.320 --> 01:03:30.810
with people.

01:03:30.810 --> 01:03:35.370
But it involves calling
people up and going--

01:03:35.370 --> 01:03:40.940
Sometimes the things
you see in here,

01:03:40.940 --> 01:03:43.750
the most non sequitorious
things you hear,

01:03:43.750 --> 01:03:49.650
and the most
meaningless gestures,

01:03:49.650 --> 01:03:53.350
it's like heroine of insight.

01:03:53.350 --> 01:03:56.610
And I don't do
research, I hang out.

01:04:03.450 --> 01:04:06.780
I'm not going to go
back to my own life.

01:04:09.390 --> 01:04:12.390
Like somebody once said,
a lot of post-World War II

01:04:12.390 --> 01:04:15.390
American fiction is vaguely
unhappy in Connecticut.

01:04:15.390 --> 01:04:17.630
I was vaguely
unhappy in the Bronx.

01:04:17.630 --> 01:04:18.630
I don't want to do that.

01:04:18.630 --> 01:04:22.430
I don't want to write about
myself, except how I filter in

01:04:22.430 --> 01:04:23.460
through my sensibility.

01:04:27.990 --> 01:04:29.380
I had notebooks,
I had notebooks.

01:04:29.380 --> 01:04:31.550
I'd scribble this down,
scribble that down.

01:04:31.550 --> 01:04:33.840
There would be a
pile like Rain Man.

01:04:33.840 --> 01:04:38.340
And I never look
at the notebooks

01:04:38.340 --> 01:04:41.880
because I figured
whatever I remember

01:04:41.880 --> 01:04:43.250
is the important things.

01:04:43.250 --> 01:04:44.940
If I don't remember
it, looking up

01:04:44.940 --> 01:04:49.510
my indecipherable
handwriting is going--

01:04:49.510 --> 01:04:50.010
Right.

01:04:50.010 --> 01:04:50.760
What's the point?

01:04:50.760 --> 01:04:51.960
OK, what did the guy say?

01:04:51.960 --> 01:04:55.200
Because I don't know if
this word is gosh or damn.

01:04:57.830 --> 01:05:00.510
You go out there
and you don't even

01:05:00.510 --> 01:05:03.040
know what you're looking for.

01:05:03.040 --> 01:05:06.850
I don't go out there with a
hit list of questions or goals.

01:05:06.850 --> 01:05:10.140
I go out there just to
be with these people.

01:05:14.220 --> 01:05:18.476
You think it was a nothing
day or a real waste of time.

01:05:18.476 --> 01:05:19.850
And then 4 o'clock
in the morning

01:05:19.850 --> 01:05:24.750
you shoot upright in bed
and you go, oh, my god.

01:05:24.750 --> 01:05:27.220
What do he say?

01:05:27.220 --> 01:05:31.960
And all of a sudden, it glink,
glink, glink, glink, glink.

01:05:31.960 --> 01:05:34.800
And I love it.

01:05:34.800 --> 01:05:37.620
I just love hanging.

01:05:37.620 --> 01:05:39.270
It's part of writing.

01:05:39.270 --> 01:05:41.040
Like I said, once
again, it's not

01:05:41.040 --> 01:05:45.240
like you have a goal of
like these big game animals

01:05:45.240 --> 01:05:46.040
you want a bag.

01:05:46.040 --> 01:05:48.850
You're just going out
there to see what happens.

01:05:48.850 --> 01:05:51.400
The danger of that is
because it's so addicting

01:05:51.400 --> 01:05:57.980
and for me it was so much fun,
I feel like I'm a student,

01:05:57.980 --> 01:05:59.070
I'm a perpetual student.

01:05:59.070 --> 01:06:04.990
And just talking to anybody
on the street in any situation

01:06:04.990 --> 01:06:06.550
I feel like I'm learning.

01:06:06.550 --> 01:06:10.300
I know this sounds a little
goody, goody, but it's true.

01:06:10.300 --> 01:06:16.120
The danger is you can get
so addicted to this game

01:06:16.120 --> 01:06:17.530
that you forget to write.

01:06:20.890 --> 01:06:26.120
It's like trying to drink
the ocean with a colander.

01:06:26.120 --> 01:06:28.570
There's just too
much world out there.

01:06:28.570 --> 01:06:32.680
And it's really hard to stop.

01:06:32.680 --> 01:06:35.890
I remember, when I was two years
on the street for Clockers,

01:06:35.890 --> 01:06:39.910
my editor said, well,
that's great, that's great.

01:06:39.910 --> 01:06:41.500
I tell them all
this amazing stuff.

01:06:41.500 --> 01:06:43.374
And he said, well, let
me ask you a question.

01:06:43.374 --> 01:06:46.050
What's the first
sentence of the book?

01:06:46.050 --> 01:06:47.695
And I immediately
had a speech defect.

01:06:47.695 --> 01:06:49.820
Well, I don't know enough
about the welfare system.

01:06:49.820 --> 01:06:52.630
I don't know about
the public defender.

01:06:52.630 --> 01:06:53.590
Just start writing.

01:06:58.150 --> 01:07:01.030
You're a lifeguard who's
a little bit afraid of sea

01:07:01.030 --> 01:07:06.260
creatures so you make it so
musclebound with experience

01:07:06.260 --> 01:07:07.940
that you can't swim.

01:07:07.940 --> 01:07:09.520
Just stop, stop.

01:07:09.520 --> 01:07:13.090
Stop pumping iron, stop
filling up notebooks.

01:07:13.090 --> 01:07:13.760
Just write.

01:07:15.380 --> 01:07:17.455
Anybody can go out and observe.

01:07:21.296 --> 01:07:22.670
It's like taking
in all his life,

01:07:22.670 --> 01:07:30.820
and now you got to shape it
into some baggy but logical

01:07:30.820 --> 01:07:35.950
beholding of a world, where
everything out there is

01:07:35.950 --> 01:07:38.890
like chaos and pinballs.

01:07:38.890 --> 01:07:42.850
And so the art is
taking all that stuff

01:07:42.850 --> 01:07:46.090
and molding it into a story.

01:07:49.420 --> 01:07:53.830
And the most dangerous thing you
can do, that I ever done is I

01:07:53.830 --> 01:07:55.570
start writing.

01:07:55.570 --> 01:07:58.780
Never, ever go back
out on the street.

01:07:58.780 --> 01:08:00.670
Guaranteed somebody
is going to say

01:08:00.670 --> 01:08:02.890
something that's going to
make you doubt everything

01:08:02.890 --> 01:08:04.900
you've ever known.

01:08:04.900 --> 01:08:06.430
It's fine, you're fine.

01:08:06.430 --> 01:08:08.830
Get away, get away
before it's too late.

01:08:08.830 --> 01:08:12.010
So you're writing and then
you start talking to somebody.

01:08:12.010 --> 01:08:14.724
And it's so dangerous.

01:08:14.724 --> 01:08:16.140
Like in seventh
grade science they

01:08:16.140 --> 01:08:18.460
try to teach you about
super saturation.

01:08:18.460 --> 01:08:20.060
So they have beaker water.

01:08:23.029 --> 01:08:23.800
It's clear water.

01:08:23.800 --> 01:08:27.640
And then they drop something
in, it turns violet.

01:08:27.640 --> 01:08:30.370
That's what going out there--
all of a sudden it's clear

01:08:30.370 --> 01:08:31.300
water.

01:08:31.300 --> 01:08:35.229
You go out there one time
too many and it's ink.

01:08:35.229 --> 01:08:36.670
And you can't see.

01:08:36.670 --> 01:08:39.729
You lose all your confidence.

01:08:39.729 --> 01:08:42.840
It's like being bold but being
fragile too because you've

01:08:42.840 --> 01:08:43.870
got to protect yourself.

01:08:48.140 --> 01:08:48.932
Thank you.

01:08:48.932 --> 01:08:50.390
I'm wondering, I'm
thinking that we

01:08:50.390 --> 01:08:52.550
should see if people
in the audience

01:08:52.550 --> 01:08:54.770
would like to ask
a question or two.

01:08:54.770 --> 01:08:58.744
I just want to say before people
ask questions, ask a question.

01:09:01.760 --> 01:09:03.080
It's happened once too often.

01:09:03.080 --> 01:09:07.609
People get up and they
have something to say.

01:09:07.609 --> 01:09:10.790
At which point, after
10, 15 minutes, you go,

01:09:10.790 --> 01:09:12.222
what's the question?

01:09:12.222 --> 01:09:14.180
And then they ask some
question that they never

01:09:14.180 --> 01:09:17.689
meant to ask just to
couch it as a question.

01:09:17.689 --> 01:09:19.880
It makes everybody
a captive audience.

01:09:19.880 --> 01:09:24.300
So I would love
to take questions.

01:09:24.300 --> 01:09:25.286
Yes.

01:09:25.286 --> 01:09:27.751
[INAUDIBLE]

01:09:27.751 --> 01:09:28.250
I'm sorry.

01:09:28.250 --> 01:09:28.749
Hang on.

01:09:28.749 --> 01:09:30.400
There's a mic coming.

01:09:30.400 --> 01:09:31.350
Hi.

01:09:31.350 --> 01:09:32.850
First of all, thanks
for being here.

01:09:32.850 --> 01:09:33.560
I appreciate it.

01:09:33.560 --> 01:09:35.359
You talk about how your
approach to writing

01:09:35.359 --> 01:09:37.760
changes when you're writing
for the screen as opposed

01:09:37.760 --> 01:09:41.676
to when you're writing
for a novel, for a page.

01:09:41.676 --> 01:09:43.300
The question was,
what's the difference

01:09:43.300 --> 01:09:47.520
in writing on the page,
screen writing and novel?

01:09:47.520 --> 01:09:50.450
Novels have language, sentences.

01:09:50.450 --> 01:09:52.160
Novels have prose.

01:09:52.160 --> 01:09:53.950
Screenplays have no prose.

01:09:53.950 --> 01:09:57.920
They are like telegrams
to the director.

01:09:57.920 --> 01:09:59.900
This guy does this,
she says that.

01:09:59.900 --> 01:10:01.530
He does this, she does that.

01:10:01.530 --> 01:10:03.120
End of scene.

01:10:03.120 --> 01:10:03.740
Next scene.

01:10:03.740 --> 01:10:07.520
Two sentences set up
the location, the move.

01:10:07.520 --> 01:10:08.630
OK.

01:10:08.630 --> 01:10:09.350
Boy.

01:10:09.350 --> 01:10:10.160
Blah, blah, blah.

01:10:10.160 --> 01:10:11.540
Girl. blah-de-blah-de-blah-blah.

01:10:11.540 --> 01:10:12.039
Boy.

01:10:12.039 --> 01:10:15.210
Blah-de-blah.

01:10:15.210 --> 01:10:17.790
They start throwing kitchen
appliances at each other.

01:10:17.790 --> 01:10:18.370
Cut.

01:10:18.370 --> 01:10:18.950
Next scene.

01:10:18.950 --> 01:10:20.180
Exterior, night.

01:10:20.180 --> 01:10:21.630
Interior, day.

01:10:21.630 --> 01:10:23.820
Blup, blup, blup.

01:10:23.820 --> 01:10:27.365
It's like Post-It notes.

01:10:27.365 --> 01:10:34.524
[INAUDIBLE] development.

01:10:34.524 --> 01:10:36.440
I guess my question was
more development wise,

01:10:36.440 --> 01:10:39.560
if I can use that term, which
comes from TV and film making.

01:10:39.560 --> 01:10:41.420
When you're going
into conceptualizing,

01:10:41.420 --> 01:10:44.120
developing a screenplay
versus conceptualizing

01:10:44.120 --> 01:10:46.370
and developing a book.

01:10:46.370 --> 01:10:48.920
I guess your approach to
plotting and to structure

01:10:48.920 --> 01:10:51.260
in that way rather
than the actual writing

01:10:51.260 --> 01:10:52.730
of a scene versus--

01:10:52.730 --> 01:10:57.710
Well, I think what happens is
the difference in consciousness

01:10:57.710 --> 01:10:59.930
is the clock.

01:10:59.930 --> 01:11:02.990
When you're writing a novel
there's no narrative clock.

01:11:02.990 --> 01:11:09.170
When you're writing a script,
or a television pilot,

01:11:09.170 --> 01:11:11.940
if you go over say an hour
and 50 minutes you're dead.

01:11:15.260 --> 01:11:18.620
If you go over 55
minutes you're dead.

01:11:18.620 --> 01:11:22.600
So you're writing with
one eye on the clock.

01:11:22.600 --> 01:11:24.450
He wants page 40.

01:11:24.450 --> 01:11:27.980
So you have to be exactly
conscious of where

01:11:27.980 --> 01:11:32.600
you are vis-a-vis the length
of the project you're writing.

01:11:32.600 --> 01:11:41.240
Novels, you could write
a 9,000-page book.

01:11:41.240 --> 01:11:44.720
The only requirement is that
it's compelling and readable

01:11:44.720 --> 01:11:48.110
and says something.

01:11:48.110 --> 01:11:51.154
And you could be more amorphous
when you're writing novels

01:11:51.154 --> 01:11:53.570
because you can have two people
sitting on a bench talking

01:11:53.570 --> 01:11:55.410
for 20 pages.

01:11:55.410 --> 01:11:57.620
And once again, the
conversation, all it has,

01:11:57.620 --> 01:12:00.680
the conversation has to be
scintillating or interesting

01:12:00.680 --> 01:12:01.790
at least.

01:12:01.790 --> 01:12:08.642
You can't do that for
film because it's not

01:12:08.642 --> 01:12:09.350
a written medium.

01:12:09.350 --> 01:12:10.460
It's a visual medium.

01:12:10.460 --> 01:12:12.320
It's a two-M dimensional medium.

01:12:12.320 --> 01:12:14.660
You hear and you see.

01:12:14.660 --> 01:12:17.390
Like I said, there's no
I wonder as I wander.

01:12:17.390 --> 01:12:20.240
In writing a script, you
have to know your story.

01:12:20.240 --> 01:12:23.300
And there's no room for, gee.

01:12:23.300 --> 01:12:25.430
You have to know
before you start,

01:12:25.430 --> 01:12:30.650
because you're in such a
small phone booth, exactly

01:12:30.650 --> 01:12:32.630
what the story is.

01:12:32.630 --> 01:12:37.700
Because you can't wander off
after 20 pages and decide

01:12:37.700 --> 01:12:40.796
you don't like your main
character in the screenplay.

01:12:40.796 --> 01:12:41.420
He'll kill you.

01:12:44.150 --> 01:12:46.070
A novel, some people
just write novels

01:12:46.070 --> 01:12:49.040
from sentence to sentence,
see where it takes them.

01:12:49.040 --> 01:12:51.080
But time is money,
and there's a lot

01:12:51.080 --> 01:12:52.670
of people waiting for a script.

01:12:52.670 --> 01:12:57.020
And it's got to be
tight, crisp, and go

01:12:57.020 --> 01:13:00.030
where it's going up front.

01:13:00.030 --> 01:13:03.715
And that's all the
difference in the world.

01:13:03.715 --> 01:13:04.450
Thank you.

01:13:10.430 --> 01:13:15.284
It feels as though
the script writing

01:13:15.284 --> 01:13:17.210
has more restrictions on you.

01:13:17.210 --> 01:13:19.790
I just think, do
you feel as if you

01:13:19.790 --> 01:13:22.460
can get your narrative
voice into a character's

01:13:22.460 --> 01:13:23.960
mouth, or not?

01:13:23.960 --> 01:13:25.310
Oh, I can.

01:13:25.310 --> 01:13:29.660
But once again, it's my voice.

01:13:29.660 --> 01:13:32.690
But who knows what the ultimate
interpretation that the actor

01:13:32.690 --> 01:13:35.120
will have or who
the actor will be?

01:13:35.120 --> 01:13:38.210
Or what the director wants,
what the studio wants?

01:13:38.210 --> 01:13:39.170
That's what I'm saying.

01:13:39.170 --> 01:13:43.040
You're the first person in and
everybody piles on top of you.

01:13:43.040 --> 01:13:48.200
And at the end of
the day, you're

01:13:48.200 --> 01:13:53.030
lucky if you feel you
recognize half of what

01:13:53.030 --> 01:13:54.810
you wrote in the final product.

01:13:54.810 --> 01:13:57.770
But if you know that going
in you're OK with that?

01:13:57.770 --> 01:14:02.090
Well, like I said, no
such thing as free money.

01:14:02.090 --> 01:14:05.724
You to make money, this
is what you got to do.

01:14:05.724 --> 01:14:06.390
We were joking--

01:14:06.390 --> 01:14:07.300
Is it painful, though?

01:14:07.300 --> 01:14:07.800
Hmm?

01:14:07.800 --> 01:14:09.690
Is it painful, or do
you just get past that--

01:14:09.690 --> 01:14:11.420
It used to be painful
when I was younger

01:14:11.420 --> 01:14:14.900
because I was so excited
about working in movies

01:14:14.900 --> 01:14:18.894
and working with people
that I've watched since I

01:14:18.894 --> 01:14:20.300
was a teenager on screen.

01:14:23.224 --> 01:14:24.890
The older I get, I'm
more philosophical.

01:14:24.890 --> 01:14:26.840
This is what I do for money.

01:14:26.840 --> 01:14:30.230
Because my name is on it
I'll do the best I can do.

01:14:30.230 --> 01:14:32.240
But I know the lay of the land.

01:14:32.240 --> 01:14:34.250
I'm not going to get
my knickers in a twist.

01:14:34.250 --> 01:14:37.350
This is what
they're going to do.

01:14:37.350 --> 01:14:39.800
And I have an
agreement with myself.

01:14:39.800 --> 01:14:41.275
If this happened to me--

01:14:41.275 --> 01:14:44.540
because movies, you can write
the best thing in the world.

01:14:44.540 --> 01:14:47.780
But they have a
change of studio heads

01:14:47.780 --> 01:14:50.320
and there's a whole new
slate all of sudden.

01:14:50.320 --> 01:14:53.870
When I did something
for CBS, they

01:14:53.870 --> 01:14:55.430
decided halfway
through the series,

01:14:55.430 --> 01:14:57.540
CBS does not want
to dramas anymore.

01:14:57.540 --> 01:14:59.150
Dramas aren't making it.

01:14:59.150 --> 01:15:01.160
Every drama has to be
converted to action.

01:15:05.400 --> 01:15:07.490
What am I, like
Hopalong Cassidy?

01:15:07.490 --> 01:15:09.470
I mean, it's like, Jesus.

01:15:09.470 --> 01:15:11.530
You don't want me
to write action.

01:15:11.530 --> 01:15:15.532
You can't tell me mid-stream
more bells than whistles.

01:15:15.532 --> 01:15:17.990
I'm not going to give you bells
and whistles to begin with.

01:15:21.380 --> 01:15:23.550
I forgot the question.

01:15:23.550 --> 01:15:24.980
Am I good with that?

01:15:24.980 --> 01:15:27.140
I realize, I want
certain things in life.

01:15:27.140 --> 01:15:30.260
I want things in
life for my family.

01:15:30.260 --> 01:15:32.780
I want things in
life for myself.

01:15:32.780 --> 01:15:35.120
I want to enjoy myself.

01:15:35.120 --> 01:15:36.350
Everything's a compromise.

01:15:36.350 --> 01:15:39.020
If I want certain things
there are certain things

01:15:39.020 --> 01:15:39.910
I have to do.

01:15:39.910 --> 01:15:41.540
It's still writing.

01:15:41.540 --> 01:15:44.060
Whatever I write, no matter
how much I complain, and nobody

01:15:44.060 --> 01:15:47.450
feels sorry for that poor little
rich girl, but no matter how

01:15:47.450 --> 01:15:49.880
much I complain
I'm still writing.

01:15:49.880 --> 01:15:52.130
I'm getting paid for writing.

01:15:52.130 --> 01:15:54.770
It might not be what
I would like to write,

01:15:54.770 --> 01:15:58.480
but I'll make it into
something I want it write.

01:15:58.480 --> 01:15:59.650
It's called first draft.

01:15:59.650 --> 01:16:01.970
After that it's hell.

01:16:01.970 --> 01:16:04.900
I mean first draft of a script.

01:16:04.900 --> 01:16:05.400
Yes.

01:16:08.376 --> 01:16:09.368
Somebody.

01:16:12.080 --> 01:16:16.640
I was wondering if you could
describe how your reading has

01:16:16.640 --> 01:16:17.390
changed over time.

01:16:17.390 --> 01:16:19.970
Because I know that
you mentioned that once

01:16:19.970 --> 01:16:22.340
you discovered more New York
and urban centric writers

01:16:22.340 --> 01:16:24.020
that you really
found your voice.

01:16:24.020 --> 01:16:27.530
But now that maybe you
have a better sense

01:16:27.530 --> 01:16:29.540
of what your voice
is than you did then,

01:16:29.540 --> 01:16:33.627
if your reading has expanded
to like other perspectives.

01:16:33.627 --> 01:16:34.710
And if that's maybe like--

01:16:34.710 --> 01:16:37.370
Has my reading broadened?

01:16:37.370 --> 01:16:40.610
Yeah, it has because I
don't need them anymore.

01:16:40.610 --> 01:16:44.390
I'm the one that the ones
coming up read, in that sense.

01:16:44.390 --> 01:16:49.220
If you're looking for somebody
that reminds you of you,

01:16:49.220 --> 01:16:52.670
if you were like me, I'm
the guy, among others.

01:16:55.310 --> 01:16:57.680
My reading has
always been eclectic.

01:16:57.680 --> 01:17:01.190
Not all reading is
for inspiration.

01:17:01.190 --> 01:17:04.640
It's because you love to read.

01:17:04.640 --> 01:17:10.070
When I'm reading to find
myself, that's more hunting.

01:17:10.070 --> 01:17:14.161
I'm not hunting anymore,
I'm reading for pleasure.

01:17:14.161 --> 01:17:14.660
What?

01:17:14.660 --> 01:17:16.590
So what are you reading?

01:17:16.590 --> 01:17:17.856
What am I reading?

01:17:17.856 --> 01:17:19.194
Sorry, I didn't--

01:17:21.900 --> 01:17:23.350
Is that Spanish Armada there?

01:17:26.630 --> 01:17:29.660
I read a hot book
about Sir Francis Drake

01:17:29.660 --> 01:17:31.920
and didn't decide
to follow up on it.

01:17:31.920 --> 01:17:33.170
I don't know what I'm reading.

01:17:33.170 --> 01:17:34.310
I'm reading everything.

01:17:34.310 --> 01:17:42.230
Because of ebooks, if you have
a really good cup of coffee,

01:17:42.230 --> 01:17:48.201
or god forbid, 5 milligrams of
Adderall, and you go to Amazon,

01:17:48.201 --> 01:17:49.700
you're going to
wind up buying seven

01:17:49.700 --> 01:17:52.560
books in about seven minutes.

01:17:52.560 --> 01:17:55.680
You're going to read maybe one.

01:17:55.680 --> 01:17:58.640
You're going to read maybe a
couple of pages of another one.

01:17:58.640 --> 01:17:59.720
And you're going to
look at the other five

01:17:59.720 --> 01:18:01.280
and say, why the
hell did I buy this?

01:18:01.280 --> 01:18:02.029
What's this about?

01:18:05.180 --> 01:18:09.119
Ebooks has ruined
my concentration.

01:18:09.119 --> 01:18:10.410
There's so much I want to read.

01:18:13.984 --> 01:18:15.150
I could be reading anything.

01:18:15.150 --> 01:18:16.800
But I'm also reading
four other books,

01:18:16.800 --> 01:18:18.591
and I'll probably never
finish any of them.

01:18:21.030 --> 01:18:23.070
There's a sadness also.

01:18:23.070 --> 01:18:24.840
Is that, when you
get older you realize

01:18:24.840 --> 01:18:27.000
you're never going
to read the writers

01:18:27.000 --> 01:18:28.350
you always meant to read.

01:18:28.350 --> 01:18:31.770
You're never going to a lot
of the writers you always

01:18:31.770 --> 01:18:34.690
meant to read because you
don't want to read them.

01:18:34.690 --> 01:18:38.970
Your rhythm, your metabolism.

01:18:38.970 --> 01:18:42.750
There are certain books you love
when you're 20, in your 20s.

01:18:42.750 --> 01:18:44.940
And it's like learning
a foreign language.

01:18:44.940 --> 01:18:50.920
Your brain is open to this
book at this time in your life.

01:18:50.920 --> 01:18:53.580
And as you get older,
I know what I like,

01:18:53.580 --> 01:18:54.780
I know what I want.

01:18:54.780 --> 01:18:57.930
I know what makes me curious.

01:18:57.930 --> 01:19:01.290
So god help me, I'll
probably never read

01:19:01.290 --> 01:19:03.230
the Mayor of Casterbridge.

01:19:03.230 --> 01:19:06.510
I'll never read a
million books that I'm

01:19:06.510 --> 01:19:08.510
embarrassed to say
I haven't read.

01:19:08.510 --> 01:19:11.220
I want to, but time is short.

01:19:11.220 --> 01:19:13.240
There are a lot of
books out there.

01:19:13.240 --> 01:19:16.840
And it's kind of like
a depressing thought.

01:19:16.840 --> 01:19:17.992
Yes.

01:19:17.992 --> 01:19:21.630
[INAUDIBLE] Price, Claire
mentioned John Le Carre.

01:19:21.630 --> 01:19:25.320
I wonder if you could
name a few other writers,

01:19:25.320 --> 01:19:28.010
who like you, have kind
of walked with a genre

01:19:28.010 --> 01:19:31.620
and yet gone outside
it wildly too?

01:19:31.620 --> 01:19:34.140
Basically, are there writers
in that particular genre?

01:19:34.140 --> 01:19:35.530
No, not in that
particular genre,

01:19:35.530 --> 01:19:36.738
but writers like you who've--

01:19:36.738 --> 01:19:37.650
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

01:19:37.650 --> 01:19:43.710
Writers like you who really have
a tricky and great relationship

01:19:43.710 --> 01:19:46.940
with genre and have gone
beyond it in great ways.

01:19:46.940 --> 01:19:48.750
I'd say Le Carre's one,
and you're another.

01:19:48.750 --> 01:19:50.340
Are there others, do you think?

01:19:50.340 --> 01:19:51.270
I'm sure there are.

01:19:51.270 --> 01:19:53.561
I can't think of any right
now, but I'm sure there are.

01:19:56.130 --> 01:20:00.615
Listen, Joseph Conrad
wrote spy books.

01:20:00.615 --> 01:20:02.240
If you want to think
about, Dostoyevsky

01:20:02.240 --> 01:20:06.210
wrote probably one of the
best murder mysteries,

01:20:06.210 --> 01:20:09.060
although you know up front who
did it, which is what I prefer.

01:20:11.700 --> 01:20:14.880
Look at the science fiction
being written by Doris--

01:20:14.880 --> 01:20:17.490
there are people
that use genres,

01:20:17.490 --> 01:20:19.050
but they're using genres.

01:20:19.050 --> 01:20:23.280
It's not like they're dyed in
the wool, loyal card carrying

01:20:23.280 --> 01:20:25.080
members of that genre.

01:20:25.080 --> 01:20:28.680
Would you call Cormac
McCarthy a Western writer?

01:20:28.680 --> 01:20:29.960
You

01:20:29.960 --> 01:20:33.060
Well, speaking more
narrowly, what about writers

01:20:33.060 --> 01:20:37.710
working as you do with
police and dead bodies,

01:20:37.710 --> 01:20:40.890
and yet writing these
novels that transcend.

01:20:40.890 --> 01:20:42.960
Are there others?

01:20:42.960 --> 01:20:48.870
All I can say is there are a
lot of people in the crime genre

01:20:48.870 --> 01:20:52.770
that are really great
writing crime genre.

01:20:52.770 --> 01:20:56.010
But they're writing crime genre.

01:20:56.010 --> 01:20:59.550
I don't know too
many crime writers

01:20:59.550 --> 01:21:04.470
who bust out of the corral.

01:21:04.470 --> 01:21:08.250
The thing about crime
writing is you can't

01:21:08.250 --> 01:21:12.360
remember who did what to what.

01:21:12.360 --> 01:21:15.530
I might read The Big Sleep
or Farewell, My Lovely

01:21:15.530 --> 01:21:18.600
or The Maltese Falcon.

01:21:18.600 --> 01:21:20.550
Who cares who did what to what?

01:21:20.550 --> 01:21:28.960
You read crime for the narrative
voice and for the atmosphere.

01:21:28.960 --> 01:21:34.310
And for creating a
memorable central character

01:21:34.310 --> 01:21:37.110
and evoking a time and a place.

01:21:37.110 --> 01:21:39.088
Everything else is popcorn.

01:21:42.920 --> 01:21:44.310
Many questions.

01:21:44.310 --> 01:21:45.931
Sir at the back.

01:21:45.931 --> 01:21:46.430
Yes.

01:21:51.780 --> 01:21:52.280
Hi.

01:21:52.280 --> 01:21:53.180
Thanks.

01:21:53.180 --> 01:21:55.280
Could you speak a little
bit about the role

01:21:55.280 --> 01:21:57.900
that drugs play in
the writing process,

01:21:57.900 --> 01:21:59.150
if they play a role for you?

01:21:59.150 --> 01:21:59.671
In drugs?

01:21:59.671 --> 01:22:00.170
Drugs.

01:22:00.170 --> 01:22:03.170
Like you mentioned
cocaine briefly, Adderall.

01:22:03.170 --> 01:22:05.000
I'm wondering if
that's something

01:22:05.000 --> 01:22:07.730
that does play a role
in the writing process

01:22:07.730 --> 01:22:09.770
in terms of creativity
or otherwise?

01:22:12.770 --> 01:22:15.800
Even William Burroughs
said he's never

01:22:15.800 --> 01:22:21.920
written any a damn page
that was any good on drugs.

01:22:21.920 --> 01:22:25.760
Apologies to Thomas De Quincy.

01:22:25.760 --> 01:22:30.440
I think drugs are the
enemy of real creativity.

01:22:30.440 --> 01:22:33.830
Not to sound like a
moralizer, but I'm

01:22:33.830 --> 01:22:35.760
haunted by my own
experience with drugs.

01:22:35.760 --> 01:22:37.680
But when I try to
write on that--

01:22:37.680 --> 01:22:40.070
Adderall, I do take
Adderall because sometimes I

01:22:40.070 --> 01:22:42.120
just feel like I don't
want to write about.

01:22:42.120 --> 01:22:43.661
But with Adderall,
it'll just give me

01:22:43.661 --> 01:22:44.730
a little bit of a boost.

01:22:44.730 --> 01:22:49.100
And so when I open it I get
lost in working really fast.

01:22:49.100 --> 01:22:53.000
But my writing is
haunted by drugs

01:22:53.000 --> 01:22:55.310
because of my own experience.

01:22:55.310 --> 01:22:59.270
Clockers, I was
just sniffing coke,

01:22:59.270 --> 01:23:04.070
like party coke when
crack came along.

01:23:04.070 --> 01:23:07.040
I finally figured out
how to make cocaine

01:23:07.040 --> 01:23:10.490
affordable to poor people.

01:23:10.490 --> 01:23:12.370
And it was 10 times deadlier.

01:23:12.370 --> 01:23:14.150
This cocaine is god's
way of telling you

01:23:14.150 --> 01:23:16.310
you're making too much money.

01:23:16.310 --> 01:23:19.130
But this is not coke.

01:23:19.130 --> 01:23:22.430
I was so haunted by my
own years on cocaine,

01:23:22.430 --> 01:23:25.820
when crack became
a phenomena, and it

01:23:25.820 --> 01:23:30.170
is the quintessence
of not the end

01:23:30.170 --> 01:23:34.640
of the world in a white rock.

01:23:34.640 --> 01:23:38.850
You couldn't read the sports
pages back in the late '80s

01:23:38.850 --> 01:23:44.170
where crack-- even you'd
say, well, Yankees 4 crack 3.

01:23:44.170 --> 01:23:47.600
Crack had just drafted
a new crack head.

01:23:47.600 --> 01:23:48.690
It was pervasive.

01:23:48.690 --> 01:23:50.150
And it just haunted me.

01:23:50.150 --> 01:23:54.470
And that drove me
to write Clockers.

01:23:54.470 --> 01:23:57.414
Like I said,
autobiography seeps in.

01:23:57.414 --> 01:23:59.580
I'll tell you my experience
trying to write on coke.

01:24:03.110 --> 01:24:06.560
Quite bluntly, I
was 30 years old.

01:24:06.560 --> 01:24:09.230
I do like to get me started.

01:24:09.230 --> 01:24:11.743
I do a line, I'd write a
line, I'd write a paragraph.

01:24:11.743 --> 01:24:13.470
I'd go, that's a
great paragraph.

01:24:13.470 --> 01:24:15.170
Let's celebrate.

01:24:17.970 --> 01:24:19.000
Write two more lines.

01:24:19.000 --> 01:24:20.720
That was a great two more lines.

01:24:20.720 --> 01:24:21.770
Anybody up for a boop?

01:24:24.570 --> 01:24:25.350
Write one line.

01:24:25.350 --> 01:24:26.150
All right.

01:24:26.150 --> 01:24:28.130
Those are great three words.

01:24:28.130 --> 01:24:29.630
Let's have a bump.

01:24:29.630 --> 01:24:38.150
And pretty soon, I started
out allegedly snorting coke

01:24:38.150 --> 01:24:39.640
in order to write.

01:24:39.640 --> 01:24:45.410
And then it got so horribly
perverted I was writing

01:24:45.410 --> 01:24:47.720
as an excuse to do coke.

01:24:47.720 --> 01:24:51.790
And at one point I'm
working on something.

01:24:51.790 --> 01:24:55.580
I had 100 pages and
each page was great.

01:24:55.580 --> 01:24:58.730
But each page was
for a different book.

01:24:58.730 --> 01:25:01.730
So it made no sense.

01:25:01.730 --> 01:25:03.620
It was too.

01:25:03.620 --> 01:25:06.825
It's like an oscillating
beer sign by the jukebox.

01:25:11.980 --> 01:25:15.710
Listen, there are
serious drugs that

01:25:15.710 --> 01:25:20.990
need to be taken by people who
are suffering from stuff that

01:25:20.990 --> 01:25:25.100
makes them drop down a hole that
nobody can understand if they

01:25:25.100 --> 01:25:27.500
haven't had that malady.

01:25:27.500 --> 01:25:31.550
[INAUDIBLE] that type of
drugs, recreational drugs.

01:25:31.550 --> 01:25:32.340
Alcohol?

01:25:32.340 --> 01:25:33.180
Nope.

01:25:33.180 --> 01:25:39.080
You can't do any of that stuff
and keep a coherent flowing

01:25:39.080 --> 01:25:40.790
mind.

01:25:40.790 --> 01:25:43.990
And that's been my experience.

01:25:43.990 --> 01:25:44.705
That's it.

01:25:44.705 --> 01:25:46.580
I wouldn't even go for
a second cup of coffee

01:25:46.580 --> 01:25:49.550
because I'll just buy
seven more books on ebooks,

01:25:49.550 --> 01:25:50.550
instead of writing.

01:25:50.550 --> 01:25:53.570
Now I've got 14 books
I'll never read.

01:25:53.570 --> 01:25:55.910
Maybe one last question.

01:25:55.910 --> 01:25:58.240
Sir here in the front.

01:25:58.240 --> 01:26:00.630
Actually do you--
no, sir, go ahead.

01:26:00.630 --> 01:26:05.480
Do you have any examples
of scripts you've written

01:26:05.480 --> 01:26:10.580
and there's a big change either
like there was a great change,

01:26:10.580 --> 01:26:13.690
or like, oh, my god, I
can't believe I did that?

01:26:13.690 --> 01:26:15.020
Could you be more specific?

01:26:15.020 --> 01:26:16.220
I'm not quite--

01:26:16.220 --> 01:26:20.060
Like if you wrote a script,
and then it got produced,

01:26:20.060 --> 01:26:20.899
let's say.

01:26:20.899 --> 01:26:21.440
I don't know.

01:26:21.440 --> 01:26:25.030
Was Color of Money was the
protagonist a 12-year-old girl

01:26:25.030 --> 01:26:26.600
originally, or
something like that?

01:26:26.600 --> 01:26:27.290
No.

01:26:27.290 --> 01:26:28.100
No.

01:26:28.100 --> 01:26:30.260
That's screenwriting.

01:26:30.260 --> 01:26:33.620
And TV writing is all business.

01:26:33.620 --> 01:26:37.670
You don't have the whim, you
don't have the power of whimsy

01:26:37.670 --> 01:26:41.630
to change your
mind because you're

01:26:41.630 --> 01:26:45.160
getting paid by people who
are creating a product.

01:26:45.160 --> 01:26:46.690
And they know the
reason why you're

01:26:46.690 --> 01:26:48.571
writing it is that
they gave it thumbs up.

01:26:48.571 --> 01:26:49.570
Yeah, this sounds great.

01:26:49.570 --> 01:26:50.550
Go do it.

01:26:50.550 --> 01:26:52.180
And you can't come
in, you know, I

01:26:52.180 --> 01:26:55.120
decided that
12-year-old girl, she

01:26:55.120 --> 01:26:58.680
should be a 400-year-old
man from another planet.

01:26:58.680 --> 01:27:00.400
It works so much better.

01:27:00.400 --> 01:27:03.530
They're going to look
at you and you're done.

01:27:03.530 --> 01:27:04.630
You can't do that.

01:27:04.630 --> 01:27:08.580
Whereas, there are some
great stories about writers

01:27:08.580 --> 01:27:13.340
who started out doing one
thing and halfway through

01:27:13.340 --> 01:27:17.830
they switch from a
car to an airplane.

01:27:17.830 --> 01:27:23.020
I had a writing teacher, who was
a mid-century British novelist,

01:27:23.020 --> 01:27:26.440
Alan Sillitoe, who wrote The
Loneliness of the Long Distance

01:27:26.440 --> 01:27:31.090
Runner, and Saturday
Night and Sunday Morning.

01:27:31.090 --> 01:27:34.150
And some of these
books were part

01:27:34.150 --> 01:27:38.880
of the black and white British
cinema of the late '50s

01:27:38.880 --> 01:27:41.210
and early '60s,

01:27:41.210 --> 01:27:48.220
And when he was writing Saturday
Night and Sunday Morning,

01:27:48.220 --> 01:27:52.420
Richard Harris played
the main character.

01:27:52.420 --> 01:27:57.230
He said, the main character
that he intended was a sailor.

01:27:57.230 --> 01:28:01.030
And he comes into a bar, I
think it was in Nottingham.

01:28:01.030 --> 01:28:06.430
So he comes into the bar and he
challenges any of these factory

01:28:06.430 --> 01:28:07.720
lugs to a drink off.

01:28:07.720 --> 01:28:09.440
I can drink any man
under the table.

01:28:09.440 --> 01:28:12.280
He said, well, now I have
to create a character

01:28:12.280 --> 01:28:14.500
to take up the challenge.

01:28:14.500 --> 01:28:16.430
So he starts writing.

01:28:16.430 --> 01:28:18.810
These guys are drinking and
talking, and this and that.

01:28:18.810 --> 01:28:21.520
All of a sudden, he
realizes, he likes this guy

01:28:21.520 --> 01:28:23.240
a lot better than the sailor.

01:28:23.240 --> 01:28:24.920
So he finished the
scene by having

01:28:24.920 --> 01:28:27.670
the sailor pass out
and get dragged out

01:28:27.670 --> 01:28:29.590
of the pub and the book.

01:28:29.590 --> 01:28:33.135
And it became about the guy
that took up the challenge.

01:28:33.135 --> 01:28:34.510
But you can do
that with a novel.

01:28:34.510 --> 01:28:35.860
It's yours.

01:28:35.860 --> 01:28:38.950
It's yours until
you surrender it.

01:28:38.950 --> 01:28:41.530
Are there any times when a
director or producer, whoever,

01:28:41.530 --> 01:28:44.410
will change something and
it was a pleasant surprise?

01:28:44.410 --> 01:28:48.730
Well, OK, glad you asked.

01:28:48.730 --> 01:28:50.701
Constantly.

01:28:50.701 --> 01:28:53.820
You write a line, you write,
who do you think you are anyhow?

01:28:53.820 --> 01:28:56.430
And it's the way [INAUDIBLE] Who
do you think you are, anyhow?

01:28:59.757 --> 01:29:00.840
But I'll tell you a story.

01:29:00.840 --> 01:29:05.680
There's a great novelist
named Leonard Gardner.

01:29:05.680 --> 01:29:10.590
And he wrote a book
called Fat City, which

01:29:10.590 --> 01:29:14.200
is about a tank town boxers,
like night of the tomato

01:29:14.200 --> 01:29:15.800
can boxers.

01:29:15.800 --> 01:29:16.730
And was Stockton.

01:29:16.730 --> 01:29:19.210
It was Steinbeck country.

01:29:19.210 --> 01:29:26.290
And it was a beautiful,
beautiful novel.

01:29:26.290 --> 01:29:31.000
Kind of Hemingway-esque
but better.

01:29:31.000 --> 01:29:33.040
And I read that book
when it came out.

01:29:33.040 --> 01:29:34.350
I loved it.

01:29:34.350 --> 01:29:36.430
And I was at a party
in San Francisco.

01:29:36.430 --> 01:29:40.270
And John Huston made a movie
out of that with Jeff Bridges

01:29:40.270 --> 01:29:41.560
and I forgot who else.

01:29:41.560 --> 01:29:42.308
Stacy Keach.

01:29:42.308 --> 01:29:42.808
Hmm?

01:29:42.808 --> 01:29:43.640
Stacy Keach.

01:29:43.640 --> 01:29:44.560
Right, right.

01:29:44.560 --> 01:29:45.910
Exactly.

01:29:45.910 --> 01:29:51.130
So I meet Leonard
Gardner at a party.

01:29:51.130 --> 01:29:55.780
And here's what you should never
say to a novelist at a party,

01:29:55.780 --> 01:29:57.474
especially when there's alcohol.

01:29:57.474 --> 01:29:59.890
So what did you think of the
movie they made of your book?

01:29:59.890 --> 01:30:05.020
[LAUGHTER]

01:30:05.020 --> 01:30:08.650
So I asked him that question.

01:30:08.650 --> 01:30:11.800
And he's built like a whippet.

01:30:11.800 --> 01:30:14.420
I think he used to box
himself at some point.

01:30:14.420 --> 01:30:15.890
He was just a coil.

01:30:15.890 --> 01:30:17.020
He wasn't even a man.

01:30:17.020 --> 01:30:21.040
He was just a coil of muscle
and tension and quiver.

01:30:21.040 --> 01:30:24.510
But when I asked that question
he literally started shaking.

01:30:24.510 --> 01:30:27.070
I thought his temples
were going to explode.

01:30:27.070 --> 01:30:29.020
He started cursing
out John Huston.

01:30:29.020 --> 01:30:31.439
That son of a bitch.

01:30:31.439 --> 01:30:32.980
Any time he thought
he could he could

01:30:32.980 --> 01:30:36.280
score a girl he gave her an
extra line that I didn't write.

01:30:36.280 --> 01:30:38.230
And he did this,
and he did that.

01:30:38.230 --> 01:30:42.340
And it was like talking to the
Ancient Mariner on steroids.

01:30:42.340 --> 01:30:43.575
And I said, oh, my god.

01:30:43.575 --> 01:30:45.700
And I was thinking of
adapting one of my own books.

01:30:45.700 --> 01:30:46.409
I had an offer.

01:30:46.409 --> 01:30:47.950
And after that, I
said, god damn, I'm

01:30:47.950 --> 01:30:51.730
never going to touch my books,
which I should have stuck to.

01:30:51.730 --> 01:30:55.360
And I said, god, I'm
so sorry, Leonard.

01:30:55.360 --> 01:30:56.579
What are you doing now?

01:30:56.579 --> 01:30:58.120
I'm writing a script
for John Huston.

01:30:58.120 --> 01:30:59.720
[LAUGHTER]

01:30:59.720 --> 01:31:01.460
And I went, oh, my god.

01:31:05.470 --> 01:31:08.390
Well, perhaps that's a
good place for us to stop.

01:31:08.390 --> 01:31:09.890
Richard, thank you so much.

01:31:09.890 --> 01:31:10.490
[APPLAUSE]

01:31:10.490 --> 01:31:12.340
It was [INAUDIBLE]

